WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Okay, we're ready.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Today is Thursday, September 1, 2011.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
I'm with videographer John Bishop.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And we are in the field today to do an oral history interview for the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:39.000
which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:45.000
And we're delighted to be in Oakland at the offices of the Black Alliance for just immigration with Mr. Phil Hutchings.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Thanks so much for sitting down.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
It's a pleasure that they be under the building.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
You caught me.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Let me start. Let's just for a few minutes talking a little bit about your family in Cleveland and coming up there.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And obviously that would be some of the on trade to all your later civil rights and other work.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Maybe just have you talked a little about your folks and coming up in Cleveland?

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Well, my folks were migrants to Cleveland.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:17.000
My dad is from Macon, Georgia.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
I just visited there pretty recently about a week ago.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
And he, as a young man, I'm not sure exactly how old he was.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
His dad and his mother divorced.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:39.000
And she stayed in Georgia and his father went up to Cleveland as part of the Northwirt Migrations and got a job as a street car conductor on Leole Trackless Trolleyes.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And by the end, it's followed him.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:45.000
I don't know exactly.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
A bunch of questions you'd love to ask later and never got around to asking at the time.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:51.000
So I don't know exactly.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
But he came as a young man somewhere to Cleveland.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
My mom was born in a little town outside of Memphis, Tennessee, Union City.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
And her mother died when she was about a year old.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:15.000
And so she was passed to one of the sisters, one of our mother's sisters, her aunt.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.000
And the aunt lived in Cleveland and was a maid in Cleveland.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And so my mom came at a very young age.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
She was too young to be even aware of it probably.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
To Cleveland and lived out in Cleveland Heights for the most part.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:38.000
She moved around as her aunt got different jobs.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:46.000
So there's a lot of interest right now because there was a domestic workers' bill of rights that was passed in New York State about a year or so ago.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:50.000
And there's one pending in the California State Legislature.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
So they're trying to look at what has been the history of domestic workers over time.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And I just said, oh, my mother wasn't a domestic worker.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:04.000
But she was the woman who raised her, was, and she used to live in the house where her mother worked as a maid.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
How interesting was that?

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Tell me something about that.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Oh, so I should just say that around that, they were, I would call, lower middle class.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:24.000
My dad worked at the post office as a clerk, pretty much all his work life.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:30.000
In the mid-50s, he did get a job as a salesman for something called Kaiser Frazier.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
You're probably old enough to know what that was.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:38.000
And that, with belly up, not too long afterwards.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:44.000
So I think that basically said, I better go back to the government where there's always a current job.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And again, one of these questions you never asked is, I'm sure a lot of that thinking was shaped by the depression.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
And again, it's something we never, ever talked about.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:03.000
But at a time in the 50s, we're in late 50s, particularly where some of his friends were beginning to become doctors or lawyers and professionals.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
I think about buying their house.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:12.000
He kind of stuck in where he was, where he felt they were sure to, assurance as a postal clerk.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So it meant being a postal clerk that he was governed by something called the Hatch Act,

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:24.000
which means that as a US postal worker, he couldn't be political activists.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:33.000
So he had a lot of interest in a lot of the questions of the day, but that's why he did it through the church.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:40.000
And there was this social and literary forum called the St. James Forum, which was not our particular church actually.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:46.000
But I'm not quite sure of the politics, but he became sure of that for a couple years.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:53.000
And it's a little boy, I would go to some of those meetings and there would be local politicians are talking about issues.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:59.000
So on one hand at a very early age, I got some sense of the bigger world.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And they were coming right to a church right in our general neighborhood in Cleveland.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And I remember meeting the late Senator Robert Taft, who was from Ohio in 1952.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
I was all of eight years old.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
And Taft was running for the Republican nomination against Eisenhower, which he eventually lost.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
But as the home senator, he was going around.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
And the church was one of the places where a lot of the white politicians came to talk to parts of the black consistency.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
And so St. James was one of the leading churches for that.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:36.000
And so they got a really good sort of, I remember shaking Robert Taft's hands.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:42.000
And I said to my dad, I said, Dad, you know, he's got the most on the softest hands.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
I had shook hands with him. I'm eight year old.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:51.000
And my dad, he was a Democrat, a queer, I said, yeah, because he's never done a real days of work in his life.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And so, okay.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
So my dad was active at that level.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:01.000
And he was a decadent in the church, but he was restricted in terms of his politics.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
So I would always thought about him.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
He was a kind of Humphrey, he was a Humphrey Democrat in the late 50s, early 60s.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.000
My mom, as she grew up, she became a social worker.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:19.000
And then she eventually went to law school.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
And she had the good fortune.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:30.000
It was one of those days where there were so few blacks moving ahead at that level that the small circles of people knew each other.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:35.000
So she ended up going to law school with Carl Stokes, who became the first black mayor of Cleveland.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:41.000
And when he became mayor, he actually appointed her the chief referee of the Civil Service Commission.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:47.000
And being a typical, I mean, my mind was in the South, what was happening in the Civil Rights Movement.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
And I guess I wasn't aware that much later on how critical a job that was,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:56.000
because they were trying to integrate or desegriate the better word, the fire department and the police.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:59.000
And so it was very much a hot seat job.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And so, but I never, again, at the time, was not totally aware of a lot of the stuff that she was having to deal with and go through

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
and Stokes being the first black mayor.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
It was just a lot of kind of almost like Obama being the first black president.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:19.000
So it was a really time for them. But as a kid, they kind of shielded that.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.000
I was aware of it, but not really aware of the deep details.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And so, they were very interested. My dad, we used to listen to Lowell Thomas on the radio as a kid.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And we had one of those old-fashioned globes on a stand.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
And after the Lowell Thomas was over, we'd go over to the globe.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:45.000
And there was something about Iran, he'd show me where it was, or Cuba.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
So I sailed that to say that I was getting a sense of the world.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:57.000
And it was right in the family. And some of the local things, there was nothing radical about Lowell Thomas.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:06.000
But at least it was the news. And Cleveland, I think, always felt itself kind of the more liberal part of the state of Ohio.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:13.000
And it tended to look east toward New York, as opposed to west to Chicago.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
And so there was a kind of liberalism in the air.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
There was a very kind of liberal Jewish community in Cleveland.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:25.000
At least at that time, I'm not too familiar with what's going on more currently.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:31.000
And there was a lot of ethnic diversity, mostly Catholic.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
And people from Eastern Europe.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:42.000
And then you had a very heavy, oriented Democratic Party machine, which most of the time I was a kid, was controlled by the Irish.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:49.000
So if you were old, anything, or you could say what county you were from in Ireland, you had jobs like that, you know.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:54.000
And my mom did get into the infrastructure a little bit in the Democratic Party.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:01.000
She actually ran for state representative. And she got endorsed by the local paper at the time at Cleveland Press.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
And she did quite well for her first time around.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:13.000
She came in, I think, about 20th. And there were the first 18 with the ones who got nominated on the Democratic's slate.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:19.000
I think it was 58. It was either 56 or 58. I'm not quite remembering.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.000
So I was in high school, and so my mom was running.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:30.000
And I helped her from the very beginning. She ran originally for a precinct committee, and the district kind of...

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:37.000
Mirror our greater neighborhood. And I was a paper boy for the Cleveland playing dealer, which still exists.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:44.000
And so I just put her campaign stuff in all the papers, especially the Sunday paper, where it was really big and stuff like that.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:52.000
And then when I went to collect money, I'd say, don't forget my mother, who she's running for this, and blah, blah, blah, blah, we would like your vote.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:10:01.000
So that was some of my first little grassroots kind of political activity, and very local.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:07.000
And then the other piece I mentioned that, because I hadn't thought about it for years, was...

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
Some of our parents wanted us to do something civic. We didn't even use the word political.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:17.000
I don't know if that was from the McCarthy period or what, but it was civics and civic interest group.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:23.000
And so they got a group of young people together and tried to figure out what to do.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And I found this word called archegos, which in Greek, I've never looked it up since then, since the 50s.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:37.000
It's something about civic duty or something being part of the polity of the society.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:44.000
And so we named the archegos club, and to save my life, I couldn't remember exactly what we did back those years.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.000
But we did meet, we did do the local projects, and raised money here and there.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:54.000
And then the other piece was for me during that time period, was the...

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
There was a group, an adult group called the council on human relations.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:04.000
And they had a youth council, and they brought people from different high schools into that.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.000
And it was a way for me to meet young people, roughly my age, all over the city,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.000
because where I live was predominantly the African-American section on the East Side.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:18.000
And again, years later, I just realized what a small portion of Cleveland.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:26.000
I actually spent 99% of my time at the East Side, and maybe when we went downtown, or went to a wall game,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:31.000
at the old stadium, it was on technically the West Side.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:37.000
But by and large, the West Side was white people, and it was a little dangerous, and we didn't go there.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And so, again, most of my life was in this small piece of geography, called certain parts of the East Side.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And it wasn't until probably my early college years as I was coming back,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
as I was beginning to realize that African-Americans were moving not so much to the West Side,

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:58.000
but the different parts of the East Side, which had been kind of off limits to me when I was a kid.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:04.000
And Mount Pleasant area, Shaker Heights, Ludlow area, and that Shaker Heights was known

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:10.000
for having the first school integration in the country during that time period.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:19.000
So, there were a lot of things that were going on, and the other piece was there was something called the World Council on Human Affairs,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
and they had different chapters at different schools.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:29.000
And different schools could, they would have a yearly mock general assembly in each school in a different country.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:36.000
And I remember in the late 50s, I was at East High School, and we were France.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:43.000
And so, this was during the French Algerian War, so we had to learn all the arguments back and forth,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:48.000
and why France was right and why Algeria was really part of France and all that stuff.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:58.000
But, again, it was like getting me into some of the broader stuff of the world, and so I looked back at it as a kind of important beginning.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:05.000
And I guess one other thing I think that probably looking at the days where it was important is my dad,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:13.000
I never could understand quite the principle of a labor union in terms of having to be having to force the joint.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:18.000
I mean, I grew up in a democracy when person would do what you want, so why do you have to join a union?

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
Why do you have to be forced to join a union?

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:30.000
So, in 58, in both, actually, California, out here in Ohio, there was a right to work on the ballot,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
and they ended up losing in both places.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And out here, that was with Mr. Nolan, was running for Senate.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:43.000
No governor, he was running for governor because he wanted to be able to command the...

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
Just trichroica, you had...

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
Christopher was the...

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
I think...

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.000
Who was the governor?

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
Good one night was the governor.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:06.000
And then Nolan was the senator, and of course you had Richard Nixon as the vice president, and they were all kind of big Republicans nationally.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And the question was, who was going to control the California delegation at the Democratic Party...

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
I mean, sorry, Republican Party convention in 1960.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
And so, Nolan decided he would just...

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:26.000
You stripped the power and run for governor, and pushed night aside and night ended up running for Senate and losing,

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:34.000
and Nolan ran for governor, and he lost, but the right to work was one of the major things, as unions really,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:42.000
probably one of the last times that unions really were able to flex their power and be a decisive factor in,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:48.000
and they were also that in Ohio, though it got less attention than what was happening in California at the same time.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:55.000
So, but my dad really convinced me, he was able to show me the important power of labor, the importance of unions,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:02.000
and why crossing a union picket ride, you know, was still awful, and I still believe to this day.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:07.000
So, that was all kind of parts of my beginnings and kind of getting out there.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:10.000
Did he... did... is he born in 1942?

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
That's right.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
I was born in the middle of Stalingrad.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:23.000
And I guess over in Pacific, there was the fights around Midway, and so a lot of stuff was going on in the world.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:29.000
We did it in Simon. I can't remember if it was in high school or college. I think it was in college.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:34.000
It was happening in the world in the year that you were born. So, it was really fascinating to go look at that,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:47.000
and read what was happening in the... particularly World War II, and the struggle for Leningrad and Georgie Zuckoff and the Red Army fighting with Nazi Army in the Viermocht.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:56.000
And, you know, and even... I think it was after 43, they cut off the World Series for a couple years, and baseball.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:01.000
So, you saw the impact the war was having, and hey, I was a little kid. I'd be born all this time.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:11.000
Did some of the major events that history textbooks would recount on US-Race relations of the mid-50s,

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:20.000
did those impress themselves really on US-A teenager, and thinking of, you know, brown beboors, Montgomery, Emmett Till, Little Rock?

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:26.000
Well, I have to a great degree with some of them did. I mean, I think it was probably the largest things that came out.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:34.000
I mean, as a young man, well, young kid, I guess, teenager, when I heard about Emmett Till, I mean, that was just frightening.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:44.000
And I should say, as I said, my mother is from Tennessee, and as a kid, the first six years of my life, every summer, we would go down to Tennessee.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
And so, of course, when I was a little kid, I wasn't aware of where too much of what was going on.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:56.000
But by the time I was about five or six, I was getting a little handle on a little small town dire right outside of not too far from Memphis,

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:07.000
and where we had family. And I never knew until later that riding on the train, I was riding in a segregated car,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:16.000
and because usually my dad would come down and take me back, and say, we'd ride back on the train back up to Cleveland from, I guess, Memphis.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:27.000
And so, I don't aware of any segregated streets or signs, and I'm sure they were there.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:34.000
But we also had a black newspaper, which I think still exists, called a call and post.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:39.000
And the call and post at that time was written, I mean, it was purful.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:46.000
And people used to sometimes be a little bit embarrassed, so they put the call and post inside the Cleveland press,

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:54.000
so if they were on the bus or public transportation, they could be reading the black newspaper, but everybody wouldn't know it unless you're sitting right next to them or behind them.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:59.000
But the call and post would have stuff that was happening in terms of the national black community.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:09.000
As I mentioned in my kind of bio, that I was part of the Youth Council of the NAACP.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:15.000
My dad was a lifetime member, though, I think he became that in the early 60s, not the actual 50s.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.000
I mean, he was a member, but I think he became a lifetime member in the 60s.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:32.000
And so we were aware, I was certainly aware of Vory Wilkins, and to a lesser degree of Walter White, who had been the leader of the NAACP before that.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:43.000
But that and the urban league were the two major black organizations in Cleveland, and from being a kid to high school, in the term period.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
You jumped in in, I guess, the spring of 60.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Right.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:52.000
I guess that would be the reaction to the green for all they came up with that.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:53.000
It was.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:19:10.000
And so part of it was kind of being in these different circles of the Youth Council of the World Affairs, but particularly the Council on Human Relations, because we did a lot of interaction between that time African Americans and Jews,

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:23.000
and some degree of Catholic schools, and two lesser degree, the more white ethnics, who were from some from Appalachia, some from the Eastern European countries, the little less.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:36.000
And again, looking back and realizing the class was a major factor, who I met at that time and who I didn't meet at that time, both on the white side, and in some ways on the black side as well.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:41.000
Those are the only tickets of race topic, as I said.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:44.000
We're back after just a quick break.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:53.000
I'd like to have you just recall being an 18-year-old, I guess you would have been, or not quite 18, maybe, but nearly.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:58.000
Those early tickets at Dimes' Door in Cleveland in the spring of 1960.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:10.000
Well, the Dimes' Door were not officially segregated. And again, didn't think about it at the time, I'm sure at the level of employment, being able to work inside the Dimes' Door as opposed to just come and eat.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:15.000
There probably was some real discrimination in segregation.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:24.000
And I learned a little bit more about that when I was living years later in the 70s Detroit in terms of what was happening in the Dimes' Door in Detroit during that same time period.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:29.000
I'm sure there's a very similar in Cleveland right three hours away.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:40.000
But I think it was just in some ways being out on the street in this case, there was wall-warfs, there was crezghies, and a store called Nizernos.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:47.000
They were all right on Euclid Avenue, and right in the heart for going from the public square to six street.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:52.000
So they were all very concentrated. So we could actually hit all three of them pretty easily.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:21:01.000
And we had signs, it wasn't that we weren't telling anybody not to go in. It was just more informational of what was happening and what these stores were doing down in the South.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:13.000
And the fact that we were doing this raised a fewer within the NAACP, and our youth chapter actually got dissolved as a consequence of that.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:21.000
Well, the NAACP was not quite prepared for more physical action.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:30.000
I mean, they saw themselves as a bunch of lawyers. This would be an enduring thing in the 60s as well.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:37.000
And in some ways, even today, they've suffered from that because a lot of illegal stuff has been officially done.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:43.000
And so what's next? And they don't have a great program for that.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:55.000
But then, they were very, because Cleveland saw itself as a liberal city, and a lot of the aspiring black leaders at that time were having what we would call today,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:03.000
kind of sweetheart deals with some of the white power elite leaders, is to have something that was just on the streets.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:09.000
And I mean, if you didn't read the science carefully, it looked like it could be a picket of a local store.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:18.000
And so the fathers in NAACP said, you know, this is not the right time to be doing this.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:24.000
They're better things we should be doing. I can't even think now what those better things are worth.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:29.000
How did you judge those, your reaction to the disbanding of the youth chapter?

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:40.000
I didn't really care. I mean, which was the other part. Part of my senior year was, I mean, luckily I was halfway decent student.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:47.000
But my mother was always afraid I'd have bad grades when you didn't get into good colleges. But I was many all these young kids.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:55.000
And there was one grouping of folks I forgot to mention called the Circle Pines Club.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:02.000
And Circle Pines was a camp in Michigan, something I had a sense of at the time it was a pinko camp.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:12.000
And more recently, that's been totally confirmed. And a couple of years ago, there was the, what's it called?

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:19.000
There's a labor thing that happens here in the Bay Area of the Year. Labor...

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:32.000
I can't think of it. But about three years ago, they did this year, but about three years ago, they had something about youth camps around the country that were basically set up by the Communist Party.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:40.000
Not so much per se around indoctrination, but basically around how people from different races could live together and stuff like that.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:45.000
And we're playing together and learning to... parents could maybe meet each other and have lifelong connections.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:57.000
So there was this young group, they were heavily Jewish, but not exclusively. And mostly white, though again, there were a few kids, black kids at that time was all white and black.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:05.000
And so I joined the club because I met one of the kids at one of the high schools in Cleveland Heights.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:20.000
So we spent a lot of social time together, beyond just the meetings. And so... and there was some interaction between all these youth council, the NAACP, the Circle Pines Club, human relations, and the council world affairs.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:31.000
And so it'd be nice to do a little chart sometime of what that was. But the point being is that I've been getting radical ideas from some of this that was beyond even at that time the mainstream.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:41.000
There was another group which was around which I kind of was aware of, but didn't get close to my mother even warned me about. Remember she's a democratic politician?

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:52.000
It was called the Fair Play for Cuba Group. And of course this is the time that Cuba 59 Fidel takes over.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.000
And so...

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.000
She was just being wary of that.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:03.000
Oh yeah, yeah. And this was a good time to say it. There were three things she told me not to do.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:09.000
She said, Philip, don't get a girl pregnant. And that was like the future and all that.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:15.000
She said, don't become a drug addict and don't become a communist.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:22.000
So I said, oh, two out of three, at least. Not bad. Not bad.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:28.000
But a lot of that advice was always with the thing that she was very much the mainstream.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:35.000
And of course, as I said, she was in this hot seat which I totally realized at the time. And so I said, oh mom, I'm okay.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:48.000
But I was getting what loosely I was reading Sea Right Mills and reading about the power elites at the time and who wasn't.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:53.000
And I tried to think, well, who would that be in Cleveland or Ohio and stuff like that.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:58.000
I had one very good friend at Oberlin College which was a nearby college.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:04.000
And there was also a long history going back in some ways to Civil War in the ground railroad.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.000
But in the 50s, it was, this guy had seen his liberal college.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:16.000
I'm not quite sure. It must have been some conference. One of those groups I mentioned where I met a guy named Charlie Butts.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:22.000
His family was Republican and he actually was back in the day where you still had liberal Republicans.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:28.000
And so he was, you know, here the democratic stuff from my parents.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:32.000
And then Charlie would come and talk about how they were trying to do something new.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:39.000
And he eventually ran for something. And I had gone to college and so I lost track of it at a certain time.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:45.000
But so there was a lot of fermentation, that's when I try to say, am I young mine?

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.000
Did you ever yourself attend Circle of Pines at Cannes?

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:49.000
No, never did.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:55.000
What's the story of how you made the decision to at ease to Howard?

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:58.000
Well, that was my mother.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:03.000
I had just assumed being in the high one and we were very rich.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:09.000
Well, but first of all, my mother convinced me that I would never get into school.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:13.000
I wanted to go to Columbia and I in New York.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:16.000
And now your grades aren't going to be good enough to me too much competition.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:22.000
So I applied for something local, Ohio State and Ohio University, which I got accepted to both of them.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:27.000
And being a small town, Athens, Ohio didn't quite turn me on.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.000
So I said, well, let's go to Columbus and check that out.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.000
So I got accepted. I actually went down there, signed up.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:43.000
I got a dorm room, even met my roommate who, and then my mother called me up and said, you're not going there.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:46.000
You're going to Howard University.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:47.000
So...

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:49.000
Was it the interview so late?

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:50.000
I'm not sure.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
It was someone of a last minute thing.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
Like I said, I was already had gone down to Columbus.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:59.000
And the school hadn't actually started yet, but I was looking at whoever some of the courses,

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:03.000
the requirements, and they said, got in the room and dorm.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:09.000
And she decided that she really wanted me to be in a place where there were younger, educated, black people,

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:12.000
part of the aspiring middle class.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:21.000
She wanted me to join a fraternity and meet nice sort of sorority girls and future wife, family,

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:26.000
people I could network the rest of my life and felt that was more realistic.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.000
And she probably was right, in some ways.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:38.000
And another hand, which was interesting at the time, is that Howard University was actually cheaper to go to.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:43.000
Then Ohio State, even being a state resident of Ohio, Howard was cheaper.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:47.000
So there was a summary of the degree of the economic work.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:51.000
So they essentially, my dad and mom, we drove out to Washington.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:58.000
And I think as a kid, I'd gone to Niagara Falls once, but that was only another big trip I'd ever taken.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:02.000
So I'm going to DC and going to the East, the nation's capital.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:05.000
And then so that's how I got out to Howard University.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:11.000
You were of course very quickly, that would be thickly involved in all kinds of unfolding,

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:14.000
civil rights activism of the early sixties.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:16.000
Was that on your mind as you drove these?

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:19.000
Did you think that was going to be a part of your college experience?

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:21.000
No, didn't cross by mine.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:28.000
I just wanted to see the capital and Washington Monument and the big city and just open to a new experience.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:33.000
And I must admit, there are times when I thought, well, what would have happened to my life if I had stayed in Ohio?

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:39.000
And God, Ohio State University graduated and stayed in the state.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:42.000
I mean, the civil rights movement did become a national movement.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:45.000
So there would have been something where that would have touched me at some level.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:48.000
And this probably given my background, I would have been interested.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:59.000
I do some folks actually at Central State and in Will Beforth, who got involved.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:04.000
Yeah, who got involved. And sometimes when I came back to visit in the early sixties, I'd check in with them

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:08.000
and just see how things were going. But it was a very different scene.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:11.000
Can I take a quick break?

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:15.000
We're back after short break.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:17.000
Mr. Herscheng, what do you want to ask?

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:23.000
It's interesting you were just saying that driving out to Washington DC, the civil rights, future one, that really the question is.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:37.000
I mean, mind it all. Tell me about how you found your new campus life and the activities, the groups and organizations you used before long.

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:45.000
What did you think became involved and that was for you very quickly, and from a lot of directing, what was the golden version?

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:55.000
Well, Washington was a great place to be. And on different levels, one is at Howard itself, it had a friend number of foreign students.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:31:05.000
And the foreign students were basically from three different areas. They were from the Caribbean, Trident, Jamaica, places like that.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:12.000
A couple of smaller islands. And then they were from different African countries, some of them newly independent.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:22.000
And the third grouping was from Iran. And I never quite understood what was the basis of them being there, not the same thing wrong with them being there.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:29.000
But those were the three groups that had some degree of critical mass. There were some students from other places too.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:40.000
But this was primarily African American school. A small number of white students who usually were doing like an exchange, maybe they're junior year, they come to Howard.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:52.000
Because it was one of the historical black universities. But even as a kid, they think they're foreign students. I think about France and Germany.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:59.000
So here I was seeing foreign students from a very, very different part of the world, and hearing it just from their mouths.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:10.000
So I'm not sure there was any per se, consolidating opinion on anything that they were saying. But it was just a different than what you'd read in a Washington Post or the start.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:17.000
Oh, I can't remember. There was another paper too in Washington at the time. And so that was one piece.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:30.000
Two, I mean, Washington, you had this new guy, John Kennedy, who was the president. And kind of after the 50s, here you had this young man, World War II hero, in his 40s.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:42.000
I was like a passing of the generations of the torch to a more, who was pushing a more activist role of government. People were coming in. A lot of intellectuals particularly, the Arthur Sylesinger's and all these folks.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:56.000
It was like change was very much in the era, I guess. And so part of being in Washington was getting kind of used to this or just appreciating it. In 60 of the year I got there, of course you had the presidential election.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:07.000
After the second debate, John Kennedy came to Howard University campus. He brought Jack with him. And I hope that you're all, everybody was looking at him. He went to the chapel.

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:20.000
And talked and we had just seen him debate Nixon. And so this was not something we were reading about in the newspaper. You know, in Ohio or some other places, this was like right here.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:34.000
A little later, a few months later, I would see Richard Nixon. And at some Republican presentation, I think it was right in somewhere in Maryland, but right in suburban Washington area in Maryland.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:46.000
So he had to speak. So I mean, all of a sudden the two guys were going to be running for the future presidency of the United States, part of my reality in a way that they would never have been in a different way.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:34:01.000
So that was very part, you know, important. And then there were different events that would happen in the early 60s, the Berlin 61, most particularly the October crisis of 62,

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:22.000
where we were all sitting around watching the Soviet boats come toward Cuba. And where they're going to be fired on. And as Washington, the US Capitol, not like Cleveland, you know, when we be a bombed and nuked. And would this be the start of World War III and different professors weighing in on their history or experience.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:28.000
So it was very much debates like what was going to happen? What should happen? Should the US do this? Should the Soviets not do that?

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:37.000
And so these were debates that would never happen pretty much in Cleveland. And so that was part of the milieu from the very beginning.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:51.000
The other piece was just being a kind of political joiner, as I always call myself. And I joined different groups. And I got involved in the student government. I ran for office, didn't win.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:35:07.000
But I was campaign manager for a guy who ran for the freshman class president. And then he ran for South Korea one again. So I was kind of like the little political genius behind the scenes, getting him elected and stuff like that.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:16.000
Who was that? His name was Nathaniel Knight. He was from Baltimore, Maryland. And by the large again, somebody that kind of lost contact with over the years.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:30.000
And tell me about, I don't understand the arc between 60 and get the fall 60 and 64 when you go to Newark.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:44.000
Because you'll have, and there's a lot that happens here, none of that will action group protests, Easter arrests and 61, not a court restaurant city.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:36:02.000
You'll go at some point to this out. You'll do a lot of work on campus to support Southern student activists. And in 64, you'll go to graduate and go to Newark.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:10.000
So what company through that arc and how you were hungier with engagement with all of these questions?

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:23.000
Well, probably the easiest way to say this is that I come out of Cleveland interested in politics. I get involved in campus politics in the school.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:40.000
Then there's this other group of folks, what's we call the NAD kids. And some of them had been to the South as early as 1960 and 61 and 61. And so they come with a different kind of experience and be on the campus.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:57.000
Some of them decide, I mean, in terms of who they are, they are interested in becoming middle class black, white. They're some of them white. And they're overholes which they use in the South and the Southern struggle.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:07.000
They just walk and be on campus. Very noticeable. Different buttons, one man, one vote, and all this. And so like, who are these folks? I got attracted to them.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:15.000
And so eventually I would join. And if anything, that's what cuts through all the rest.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:36.000
I think what I learned originally from the NAD folks is that politics should be about something. It's not just politics that, well, you're my friend. I'm going to make you president of the class student class or let's see how much money we can raise for the Catillion, the dance and swap alliances between the deltas and the amegas.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:51.000
And the campus threats is that there were some bigger things that politics, getting power, getting influence, and authority should be about. And I think that probably more than anything else attracted me to these so-called NAD kids.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:38:04.000
Most of them were, well, good majority of them, not total, were from the Northeast, New York, in some ways. And then that grouping you had people like Stokely Carmichael, who came out of the Bronx, who I met in my freshman year.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:18.000
And people, yeah, Courtly Cox, of course, was there. We still call them sea cocks. And Ed Brown, who was the older brother for Rap Brown.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:35.000
And the people who were part of the early freedom movement still were keeping one foot in school, at Howard, and then in the summers they'd go south. And so this was a whole new lifestyle. You do this, okay.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:46.000
You don't necessarily go straight through school and get your four year to BA, but you may or may not. It was more important than what's happening in the south. That kind of scratched me.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:39:00.000
And I always say this when I talk to people, and love us, but the thing is that Washington was the middle ground between the so-called urban north, Northeast, and the south. And in some ways geographically, and culturally, was part of the south.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:20.000
But it was neutral, in some sense, that you were out of the south. And so a lot of people who were, we were meeting a lot of folks in the Senate movement who would come up to Washington to catch a breath of air, maybe raise money, do few fundraisers, maybe get a chance, run up to New York, but basically DC would be their headquarters.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:28.000
And so I'd be talking to these people, and hearing what they were saying, their experiences. The ones that were most really got me were the high school students.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:47.000
Because here I was in college, and I'm older, and I'm reading about government 101 and political scientists and state government that. And these are young folks who are challenging all this when they're alive.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:40:05.000
And so, the slogan was, put your body on the line. So it was like, it's a word that some of my SDS friends came out with later, called MindFuck. And that's what it was. It just totally turned up my whole idea of what was the proper order.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:28.000
And I was coming out of Cleveland and kind of aspiring black middle class, and my mother's training, I was supposed to go get a BA, meet a nice girl, get married, become a professional, get my master, maybe even doctorate, have kids, and maybe somewhere when I'm in my mid to late 30s, maybe a little no-bless oblige out there.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:42.000
So maybe do something, join the NAACP, or get active in the community. But it was basically a life of preparation. And these were folks who were doing something right now. They weren't reading to get prepared.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:55.000
And they were changing history, engaging that, and you're reading in the paper. The segregation laws were being challenged in Virginia, right next door, or Maryland.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:41:04.000
And that was totally exciting. And just seemed like the right thing to be doing at the same time. I mean, why wait when the issue was right now?

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:15.000
I guess I would read later, Martin Luther King's great thing, why we can't wait about Birmingham, but the same kind of argument. The struggle is now we have to basically put ourselves out there.

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:26.000
And we may suffer consequences, but that's the risk. But that's what the risk you take for freedom. And so that really drew me into a lot of the other things.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:35.000
So specifics were, we had created something, once I joined NAACP and got into this part of the group and was learning and doing it at the same time.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:43.000
We were staying and having late night conversations in the dorm. And I was learning, there was one very influential person named Tom Khan.

00:41:43.000 --> 00:41:56.000
He was white. He was a little bit older. He was from New York. He was with the League for Industrial Democracy, which clearly had a left background. His personal politics were kind of extratzkyite.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:08.000
And he had been very much influenced by Max Shackman, who had been in the Communist Party and then had left and formed what was called the Shackman Tendency, which went into trot schism.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:20.000
But Tom was one of the first people who had said out and talked to me about the history of the US left. And something I would never have gotten quite in the same way by reading a book about it.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:29.000
And Stokely never had time to do that. He used too much action person. And we have conversation, but other kind of conversations.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:42.000
Like are you coming to the M.O.? How many people can you bring? Can we get money from the student government to do this? Since food and clothing to Mississippi? Those kind of conversations.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:56.000
But Project Awareness, which Tom formed, and we were all part of each other's things, brought controversial speakers to Howard campus.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:13.000
The first one we brought Malcolm X. And of course the Howard University campus father, ship in their pants. And so knowing that, we tempered a little bit to have it into a debate.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:22.000
And so we brought Byrd Rustin down, who was in some ways the godfather and mentor for a lot of these younger people from the New York crowd.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:36.000
And it became one of my mentors also to basically debate Malcolm X. And so we got a huge turnout. And that established Project Awareness on the campus.

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:47.000
And then we also brought Herbert Apthacher, known communist, and the idea of having an actual real live communist. Howard University got a lot of federal money. That was what made them nervous in many ways.

00:43:47.000 --> 00:44:04.000
And then also some of them had gone through the McCarthy period. And that's a whole other side story of how some of the brilliant minds in the political science department were writing treatises on, you know, little like how does my flower grow during the 50s because they were totally scared to lose their jobs and stuff like that.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:15.000
And I mean, they could talk about in the classroom, but they couldn't really publish and put their viewpoints out and stay at Howard and feed their families and pay their rent and all that.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:22.000
So you got to see some of the repercussions also taking political stands. And that was important as well.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:29.000
So how about the experience of being arrested and you can stop yourself?

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:42.000
Let me ask you about the impact on you of the experience of being arrested, of being in demonstrations, of to shift from thinking about one set of issues in political involvement on one hand and then this action.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:49.000
Change now on the other, the whole of the impacts on you of that shift in what you were doing.

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:57.000
Well, you know, I talk about this a lot to some of the students today and it was a dramatic impact and basically it's freedom.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:06.000
My personal freedom because I became my own person. And I got arrested at a place in Baltimore, Maryland.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:14.000
We worked a lot with the Congress of racial equality. It was led by a guy named Julius Hobson at the time, who somewhat of a national spokesman in court.

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:29.000
And given that these were, the court was mostly middle class professionals. They needed basically some soldiers who could basically afford to get arrested or even demonstrate during odd hours.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:41.000
So they called up NIG in DC or they did some things in DC but one of the things we were doing was Baltimore, I mean, sorry, Maryland was officially a segregated state.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:51.000
And so it was Virginia. And we would go over to Virginia, go to some of the movie theaters because Blacks either had to sit in the balcony or they could only go on certain days.

00:45:51.000 --> 00:46:01.000
And this was like false church and Arlington and places really close to the DC. And so segregation wasn't just something you'd read about.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:07.000
It was just, you know, just really right across the state line.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:19.000
Maryland, we had this Saturday in the spring of 1961. And we, I got assigned with a small group of people to go to this place called the White Race Inn.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:36.000
That was a Chinese restaurant. And Maryland had the state accommodations law, which they could serve whoever they wanted to. And if there was any troublemakers that basically the older or the proprietor would come out, read the site to law or read it.

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:41.000
And if you didn't leave in five or ten minutes, they'd call the police and you have you arrested.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:54.000
So this particular day we went to the White Race Inn. We sat down, kind of, we weren't going to get served, but we just kind of were looking at the menus and having side conversations.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:47:03.000
So it was a racially mixed group. I remember there was about, I think there were five or six of us and at least there were two white people. One was a woman, one was a guy.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:13.000
And I can't remember if they were from Washington schools or from Baltimore schools. This can't remember that. And so we sat there for about maybe half hour.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:16.000
And so the guy checked, he was getting nervous. And so finally he comes over and says,

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:29.000
he's Chinese. And says, look, I sympathize with your cause. And one time he said, I'm a colored man, too. And he actually said that.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:40.000
But this is bad for business. I'm getting trouble. Could you please leave? And he said, no, we're going to sit here for a while.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:46.000
And so finally he gets really desperate and he comes up and says, look, I'll make a deal with you.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:59.000
I have another restaurant over in other side of town. And it's called the Brown Rice Chinese restaurant. And if you go there, I'll call ahead.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:07.000
It's all on me. I'll pay for your meal, your lunch, whatever. And just go there and it'll be all over.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:15.000
And we said, not today. Should have said, take a rain check though. We didn't think to say that. But we said no.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:22.000
So we said it for another while. So finally he has to do the do his duty and bring out the public accommodations and read it to us.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:31.000
And so he reads it to us. And we said there for about 10 minutes and saying, you should have called the police.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:40.000
Well, I think we've accomplished what we set up to do here today. We've disrupted his business. He's totally freaked out on us and stuff like that.

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:50.000
He's not doing any real business and other people keep looking at us and wondering if there's going to be some confrontation with the police and they're nervous and some people decide not to come in and all that.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:49:01.000
So we decided to leave. So we walk outside and we look at each other and we just said, we just messed up here.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:10.000
We're supposed to get arrested or at least bring the police out. And we have just literally, I think the phrase we use at the time was we just punked out.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:26.000
And probably wouldn't say that quite now, but that's what we said then. And in that I came to mind all these young high school students who I had seen and was telling you about that I admit and Howard who are younger than me who are getting arrested.

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:33.000
And hard on they going to look up to us when we're afraid to do stuff.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:39.000
So we decided just there someone said, I think it was a young woman. She said, let's get arrested.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:48.000
So we just literally sat down on the stairs in front of his restaurant. So people would have to climb in and climb out of us around this so it couldn't get in.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:59.000
And of course, he freaked out the restaurant owner. So he called the police and we just we linked arms and the police couldn't pull us apart.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:06.000
So they had a call another police car and then the patty wagon and then eventually they got us apart and we got us in jail.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:14.000
But we got a little roughed up a little bit taking and putting us in the patty wagon. Not anything serious.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:20.000
And it says what I said to them were women. We said, watch out for her. Don't have her there and all that kind of stuff.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:32.000
But what I realized was that all of a sudden something was more important than going back to do my assignments at Howard for the weekend.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:48.000
Something was more important than maybe a party that might be happening Saturday night. Something was more important than what my mother might think about my future or how this might fall at her career and all that.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:55.000
And that's what I mean about liberation. It was real sense that all of a sudden I was making a stand. It could have been about something entirely different.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:51:04.000
But I was making a stand from what I wanted my life to be about and while I was aware of other opinions, I was doing what I really wanted to do.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:13.000
And I was willing to take whatever responsibilities in this case getting arrested for it. So in that sense it was really, it was crossing a Rubicon of sorts.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:23.000
And it was very much saying this is my life. And I'm going to live it and take the consequences. And it was very much of our freeing kind of thing. That's why I met my freedom.

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:26.000
Let me touch on a few things and then we'll pick up the narrative again.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:37.000
Does anything happen in the classroom at Howard that's really pushing you forward in these ways too? Or you had earlier said that there's kind of a disconnect there.

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:46.000
Was there anything, any faculty, any class that made a difference in the sense of really living in an intellectual perspective?

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:50.000
Not really. It's somebody that I was very disappointed with Howard.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:52:05.000
I thought of us kind of like a 13th grade. You go through 12 grades of high school, then 13th grade. And then I guess after I read Ralph Ellison's invisible man, I said, what this looks like, it's like one of these newly developing countries in Africa.

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:19.000
And it felt very colonial in some sense. One because we were getting money from the federal government. The administrators were very worried about what the real powers to be were thinking and doing.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:34.000
The first couple of years I was taking requirement courses, biological science, chemical stuff. And there was a political science teacher I liked. His last name was Martin. He was Robert.

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:47.000
And he was active in the local Democratic Party in DC. That was somewhat interesting. And as I got a little further along, there were a couple of teachers. One was very fascinating. And I didn't bring a false.

00:52:47.000 --> 00:53:02.000
Paul was a Frenchman who had fought in the French resistance. And he also had been involved in Vietnam and Algeria. And so he brought a certain kind of sense to the courses as classes that you would get from anywhere else.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:13.000
I mean, so listening to him talk, we could have been at Harvard University or anywhere. And we knew we were getting a first class thinking about this.

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:24.000
But by and large, the classes were at this point. I even took a course in what was then called Negro History. And it was totally boring. It was all about dates.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:40.000
And well, in 1615, what happened in the Songai Empire? And no sense of context. What was happening in the bigger world? That was shaping Africa or that Africa was dealing with. Or it was like history with no politics.

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:55.000
And I mean, that would change particularly in the late 60s. Both in Howard and other places with black studies and the whole different focus. But I didn't get it there. And I reflect I remember in November 63 when Kennedy got killed.

00:53:55.000 --> 00:54:05.000
We were all on the campus. And I affect that was a Negro History class. And they just told us to all come out on the campus, the whole school.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:16.000
And because I wanted just to say what had happened one time. And in terms of President Kennedy. And so we were all on the campus.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:32.000
But it was a boring campus. I mean, interesting people. Both some of the professors and stuff like that. But just the arrangements of being able to teach and going through the regiment was very limited.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:44.000
I'm really interested in having stuff and reflect a little bit about the gender dynamics inside the movement in these years. And you were experiencing the way campus and you engage in the mathematics.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:47.000
Of course.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:55:01.000
We didn't think about gender. And that said it wasn't a big problem. I mean, I said as a man, of course, too. But women were very much around, very active. They weren't being secretaries.

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:16.000
And in fact, when I first joined NAG, a woman named Jeannie Bell, who I again lost contact with was one of the leaders of the local, she and Bill Mahoney were kind of a key leaders of NAG at that time period.

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:31.000
There were women who like Jean Wheeler from Detroit, who would go south, she would marry Frank Smith, who also went south, who later, Frank Smith would later become a DC city council person.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:51.000
Ruth Howard, another person who was good friend of mine, who was very active. And some others that maybe write the second or the coming of the mind. And then because at a certain point, NAG never got recognized on Howard's campus, which we always try to get recognized.

00:55:51.000 --> 00:56:03.000
And at a certain point, we realized this was a good thing. We were not getting recognized because once we got recognized, the other reason we got recognized is that we could have meetings on campus and we could get campus money as a student group.

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:13.000
And we quickly realized there are much more important things to do than either one of those two. And we'd have meetings out in people's homes, out in other campuses.

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:34.000
We met with kids from Georgetown, American University, George Washington, Catholic University, in a way that if we had been just a one school, whatever happened, that's why in my bio, I have about the DC students for civil rights. That's kind of came out of those connections.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:47.000
And we didn't have to answer anybody in terms of what we could do, where we could meet and all this, what happened as a student group. So it became a very good thing not to get.

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:59.000
Yeah, let me just to mention there's a child who would go down to the Tennessee.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:14.000
But what I did do is I did go back to Tennessee because it was one of the summers. I want to say, yeah, it had to be 62 because 63 I was doing my channel watching and stuff.

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:27.000
But I wanted to see as a young man, stuff I had seen or missing as a young kid. And there was a little bit of movement, not a big movement in Memphis at the time. And particularly not in a smaller town.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:45.000
I was my cousins. And so that was the official reason to go and see cousins and I had kind of a big older cousin, I always call her big sister. She's still alive, 10 years older than me. She lives in St. Louis now. But she saw as a house in dire Tennessee.

00:57:45.000 --> 00:58:03.000
So I just go around and all of a sudden I did see the segregation signs. I did see white people, somehow I must have seen as a young kid that didn't really dawn on me because it was pretty much like a black world, world that I was kind of in as a young kid.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:13.000
And then I saw some of the reaction where some of the folks were trying to do something around somewhere, right? And the voter registration and the harassment they were getting.

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:18.000
So that was, I mean, just as like revisiting my past, but in a different way.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:37.000
I'd love to have you describe your experience in the SIPIAN64 because you helped with the MFPP efforts. That of course concludes that sort of has that great debacle of the climax in Atlanta City.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:51.000
Well, going to the MFPPAN64 was, I went slightly limited in terms of I was working on something very particular. So there were friends I knew from NG who had gone as I mentioned in the summers.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:59:00.000
And so I went to a couple of projects mostly in the second Congressional District. One of them was Ruleville where Mrs. Hammer was, Fannie Lou Hammer was.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:15.000
And I do a lot of the staff people. Stokely was doing stuff. And Ivan Hodonelsson was around. Some other people I'm not thinking about at the moment.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:29.000
And so, but my focus was to try to work with the end of the Mrs. SIPI Freedom Democratic Party with the focus on the challenge that was coming up in later that year.

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:41.000
And what we wanted to do, because nobody trusted state officials, is we wanted to get the records of people who registered the vote and basically get their signatures, make duplicates, and then take them out of the state.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:55.000
And so I was kind of in and out going to different projects, but sitting in a lot of meetings. And also particularly with the people going out to see people who were doing voter registration. But really being in the community meetings.

00:59:55.000 --> 01:00:24.000
I mean, I probably the thing that I think about that I value the most was seeing people making attempts to do democracy at the very most grassroots level. And also the other piece which was probably in the long run even more important, like when I compare them, is people being able to have complicated discussions with basic language with people who hadn't gotten through probably even high school.

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:38.000
And so, but how do you do that kind of conversation without dumbing it down? And that was, and you can only do that from the standpoint of organizing and developing relationships, because part of it was learning how people use language.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:50.000
And so you couldn't just come down and talk or even, because then you say, oh, these poor people, they only have six grade or less education. So I have to talk in one syllable words.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:01:09.000
And that's the wrong approach. The only one that somebody could just coming in for a quick visit naturally with no I think. So our approach was from organizers who had been there, at least all summer, maybe several summers. Some people just decided to be there and dropped out of school.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:30.000
And the work on this is that you were able to know how people thought of their thinking patterns, how they approached ideas, what was the language they used around those ideas. And then how to, so in that language, wasn't so much like a foreign language, but it was kind of dialect at some level, is to basically talk about

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:48.000
the addressing devote state government, and particularly a restrictive state government. And what were some options around strategy in a ways that appeal to them and where they could participate. And I think, you know, that's probably the greatest lesson I learned.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:02:14.000
And you know, watching Mrs. Hamer, you know, just talk to people, sometimes break out into a song. And the song would be not just a song, it would be a reflection of the boot in the room. And therefore the words would pick up on what people were thinking about, feeling about, maybe wanting to do, maybe scared, whatever. But maybe you couldn't just say that in a conversation.

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:26.000
So you had to take a song to do that and sing the power of how that cultural manifestation is able to be used in a very political way. That was the profound learning.

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:38.000
I've been asked, and just not incidentally I think, you had come up in the church and believed by that, I guess, what were you, will you have set up yourself at the time that you were a person of faith? Is that a part of the culture?

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:55.000
No, no, no, I wouldn't tell you at all. I thought church was pretty boring too. I like Sunday school because it was about history. Now the Philistines and the Israelites and the Romans and all that, but I could, yeah, so I could follow that. But I never really felt that God was in our church.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:04.000
It was a nice church, middle class church is still there, and it's in the University Heights Circle Brother in Cleveland. But it ain't got supposed to be everywhere.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:20.000
So why do I have to go to that church at 11 o'clock in the Sunday morning to be in God's presence when I could do that at home or be with some friends or we could have a meeting on the park and do the same kind of thing, but why this church business?

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:30.000
Did you find yourself in a place where you had to be because you were in the circus and was fearful, actively fearful for you?

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:39.000
Oh yeah. What are the things actually that we're doing right now, relatively speaking? Is the berry of veterans of the Civil Rights Movement?

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:48.000
We're actually doing, we take records and discussions of dead and now and all that, and one of the ones we're doing is around fear in the movement.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:04:00.000
And I mean, it's impossible. I mean, Mississippi, I mean, need us some own, set it, you know. Alabama's bad, Georgia's awful, but Mississippi, God damn. And it was like the worst.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:11.000
And you were literally going into a battleground and the only comparison that I've been able to get in terms of conversation or listening, because I never went to Vietnam.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:22.000
I went to the whole another story, but it's talking to people who were in Vietnam and just the fact that they were in a pressure cooker. There was no way to get out of it.

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:47.000
And it's anything could happen at any moment. And that's the closest I felt in terms of the Mississippi experience. And then I didn't stay there that long, but talk to people, my friend who's here now, a guy named Wazir Peacock, Willy Peacock, who's from Mississippi and talked about being a Civil Rights activist in that kind of pressure cooker or people like Hollis Watkins who's still down there with group called Mississippi Echo even now today.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:59.000
It's like, this is a war zone. And you can get killed anytime. Sniper could get you just like in Vietnam or it could be straight out of salt.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:11.000
We had to know how to talk to the state officials who would come out after you and tell you to get out of town. And yet you had to stay there, but also not directly confront them.

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:22.000
And so they had to do something to get out of town and I went on one, because they had the guns, they had the law, they had everything. And they had to FBI watching, but doing nothing.

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:27.000
So yeah, it was literally a pressure curve.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:32.000
I mean, that's why to something where we lived together in project houses, part of it was

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:36.640
that if I was living by myself, I'd be totally freaked out.

01:05:36.640 --> 01:05:44.640
And I guess about my whole time in the movement, I publicly say as a way to get people thinking

01:05:44.640 --> 01:05:48.920
is that 90% of the stuff I did there in the movement I probably would never have done

01:05:48.920 --> 01:05:50.480
on my own.

01:05:50.480 --> 01:05:54.080
And I could only even just think about it and sum it up the courage to do some of this

01:05:54.080 --> 01:05:58.080
if there were other people who were involved with me and we were doing it together.

01:05:58.080 --> 01:06:02.960
And so I say that to younger people today and even some adults as a way to think about

01:06:02.960 --> 01:06:04.760
you don't have to do this all by yourself.

01:06:04.760 --> 01:06:09.560
And part of the power of being able to fork for social change is that you have people

01:06:09.560 --> 01:06:11.960
in some institutions, not a whole lot.

01:06:11.960 --> 01:06:15.360
And the South, the church was very important when it was kind of a sanctuary.

01:06:15.360 --> 01:06:20.520
But you know, that really gave us some degree of backbone.

01:06:20.520 --> 01:06:24.920
So with times when people were in jail, they'd sing and drive the jailers crazy.

01:06:24.920 --> 01:06:28.800
So they would be glad to give us out of there because that's not making so much noise.

01:06:28.800 --> 01:06:31.920
But it's like I couldn't see you, but I could hear you sing in.

01:06:31.920 --> 01:06:36.200
And so Paul and Silas, bound in jail, then you'd do the next verse.

01:06:36.200 --> 01:06:39.480
So we were creating community right in the jail.

01:06:39.480 --> 01:06:42.160
And so I mean that felt that fear though.

01:06:42.160 --> 01:06:43.160
That's what it was about.

01:06:43.160 --> 01:06:44.160
It was about just singing.

01:06:44.160 --> 01:06:46.760
That was about fighting fear.

01:06:47.160 --> 01:06:49.720
I remember getting tear gas in Cambridge, Maryland.

01:06:49.720 --> 01:06:51.560
And what was that?

01:06:51.560 --> 01:06:52.560
64.

01:06:52.560 --> 01:06:54.560
George Wallace came to town.

01:06:54.560 --> 01:06:56.080
Cambridge, Maryland, Eastern, Shore, Maryland.

01:06:56.080 --> 01:06:58.080
I guess he was running for president.

01:06:58.080 --> 01:07:02.080
That was tough fighting in Cambridge.

01:07:02.080 --> 01:07:08.080
Yeah, and so we were off there marching on the front lines and you saw the National Guard.

01:07:08.080 --> 01:07:14.760
And they were pointing these turned out to be tear gas canisters at us.

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:16.920
And we couldn't stop marching.

01:07:16.920 --> 01:07:21.680
So we started saying, we are not afraid.

01:07:21.680 --> 01:07:24.120
And keep marching.

01:07:24.120 --> 01:07:26.440
And of course we got tear gas.

01:07:26.440 --> 01:07:28.360
But again, we clutched and helped each other.

01:07:28.360 --> 01:07:32.880
The guy named Ritchie Robinson, who was in SNCC and he's now in DC.

01:07:32.880 --> 01:07:38.560
And we were right together and we fell together and we kind of staggered out of the crowd

01:07:38.560 --> 01:07:42.560
and back to safety that night.

01:07:43.560 --> 01:07:49.760
And Rat Brown was there and he got arrested, or re-arrested, probably more accurately.

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:56.160
And I remember I went back to Howard University in my fatigues and tear gas.

01:07:56.160 --> 01:08:02.200
I went straight to my ROTC class and deliberately went to smell up the whole place.

01:08:02.200 --> 01:08:04.000
Okay, Hutchings, where have you been?

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:05.000
We were in ROTC.

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:07.240
Yeah, he had to be, it was a mandatory.

01:08:07.240 --> 01:08:08.240
For two years, yeah.

01:08:09.240 --> 01:08:20.240
Did Atlantic City, was it a point of transition for you or a point of continuity?

01:08:20.240 --> 01:08:25.360
Well, it was kind of newly insensitive to another part of the struggle.

01:08:25.360 --> 01:08:33.080
But just given what happened there and that the MFDP did not get seated and people left,

01:08:33.080 --> 01:08:36.240
there was a real depression that settled on the movement.

01:08:36.240 --> 01:08:44.280
And you know, I think that right away, I mean, I was sorry that we didn't admit that

01:08:44.280 --> 01:08:48.440
practical politician part of me is like, if we only had done this or this or this, of

01:08:48.440 --> 01:08:53.320
course, but we were dealing with Lyndon Johnson.

01:08:53.320 --> 01:08:58.240
And so probably in the long run wasn't possible.

01:08:58.240 --> 01:09:02.320
And so I think it sank in at a later time.

01:09:02.320 --> 01:09:10.800
And I remember when my mother died, much later, in 1991, as I went out to Cleveland and

01:09:10.800 --> 01:09:15.400
went to the funeral, I'm only a child, did all this stuff.

01:09:15.400 --> 01:09:20.680
And then I took care of the burial, met with the minister, all that.

01:09:20.680 --> 01:09:24.040
Good soldier came back to California.

01:09:24.040 --> 01:09:28.440
And I was doing consulting at the time, so I had to get my back on stuff.

01:09:28.440 --> 01:09:31.320
And all of a sudden, my body just closed down on me.

01:09:31.640 --> 01:09:33.760
It's like say, okay, you want to do all that stuff?

01:09:33.760 --> 01:09:35.320
I'm not moving.

01:09:35.320 --> 01:09:40.680
And for like two weeks, I just sat in the house and basically mourned my mom.

01:09:40.680 --> 01:09:44.200
And I think something not quite as dramatic, but something very similar happened in the

01:09:44.200 --> 01:09:45.200
same way.

01:09:45.200 --> 01:09:47.200
It was a little delayed reaction that's what I'm going to say.

01:09:47.200 --> 01:09:50.000
And it was like, literally, what to do next.

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:56.480
And as you saw from my bio, I went back to North and where some friends I had from again

01:09:56.480 --> 01:10:00.800
from the NAG days, and ended up working for Robert Kennedy.

01:10:00.800 --> 01:10:06.400
And in a very interesting position as a research, research in Speaker's Bureau, because he was

01:10:06.400 --> 01:10:11.400
running against a liberal liberal republican kind of kidding.

01:10:11.400 --> 01:10:15.240
And somehow beyond the hype of being a Kennedy, you had to kind of say, well, what's the

01:10:15.240 --> 01:10:20.440
difference between being a liberal republican and a liberal democrat?

01:10:20.440 --> 01:10:24.760
And so that's the research part that came in very useful in being able to do that.

01:10:24.760 --> 01:10:27.880
And of course, the speaking part was to go out and basically speak.

01:10:27.880 --> 01:10:32.400
And all of the people around at that time, I mean, I was feeling that Kennedy was probably

01:10:32.400 --> 01:10:37.200
Robert, even though we used to call them all kind of names when we couldn't get any

01:10:37.200 --> 01:10:42.800
trekkles assistance down in the Cecippi or the South, is that he at least understood what

01:10:42.800 --> 01:10:44.560
that experience was.

01:10:44.560 --> 01:10:49.400
And he was growing as you know, later things, and that he could become more than he was

01:10:49.400 --> 01:10:50.400
at the time.

01:10:50.400 --> 01:10:52.200
And nobody else quite seemed to have that.

01:10:52.200 --> 01:10:56.240
And so being a Kennedy, he would make a major mark on the Democratic Party and maybe

01:10:56.240 --> 01:10:57.240
the country.

01:10:57.240 --> 01:11:00.240
And so that was kind of my rationale for working in that campaign.

01:11:00.240 --> 01:11:05.560
But it was also, it got me out of Mississippi, it got me out of that funk and basically put

01:11:05.560 --> 01:11:07.040
me in a different situation.

01:11:07.040 --> 01:11:09.360
How did you find your way to Newark?

01:11:09.360 --> 01:11:18.480
Well, that's, it's fairly immediate because I went to Newark in December of 1964 and

01:11:18.480 --> 01:11:24.760
the election for Kennedy was November of 1964, of course, right across the river.

01:11:24.760 --> 01:11:28.120
But this has to do another little piece.

01:11:28.120 --> 01:11:32.560
I guess I think I'm one of a few people in the movement who was both an SDS and a stick

01:11:32.560 --> 01:11:34.040
at the same time.

01:11:34.040 --> 01:11:37.240
I had this really crazy idea, which didn't really work out.

01:11:37.240 --> 01:11:42.480
It was interesting is that a stick was mostly active as organization.

01:11:42.480 --> 01:11:45.400
So somehow I would do my action and a stick.

01:11:45.400 --> 01:11:50.760
And then I, SNCCS did a lot of these working papers on state and society, America and the

01:11:50.760 --> 01:11:51.760
New Era.

01:11:51.760 --> 01:11:53.720
What was the meaning of corporate liberalism?

01:11:53.720 --> 01:11:56.120
All of that interesting stuff.

01:11:56.120 --> 01:11:58.920
Guy named Richard Flax, who's hit down in Southern California now.

01:11:58.920 --> 01:12:01.520
It was one of the key people, Tom Hayden.

01:12:01.520 --> 01:12:09.320
And back in 1964, early 1964, I got up to Ann Arbor, Michigan for a conference that they

01:12:09.320 --> 01:12:11.040
were putting on.

01:12:11.040 --> 01:12:13.800
And I got to meet a lot of these people.

01:12:13.800 --> 01:12:17.480
One of my good friends, who was part of the old Circle Pines group in Cleveland, named

01:12:17.480 --> 01:12:23.040
David Strauss, was a student at the University of Michigan.

01:12:23.040 --> 01:12:29.280
And he was also very active in the voice chapter, the student group, SDS political party at

01:12:29.280 --> 01:12:30.560
UBM.

01:12:30.560 --> 01:12:36.360
So through him, I got to meet people like Tom Hayden and Al Haber, who were the former

01:12:36.360 --> 01:12:39.640
of SDS.

01:12:39.640 --> 01:12:42.520
So I said that's where that piece started.

01:12:42.520 --> 01:12:47.880
And then I got to know some of the SDS people in DC.

01:12:47.880 --> 01:12:51.200
It weren't that many, mostly around George Washington University.

01:12:51.200 --> 01:12:55.240
And they mostly were in the peace movement.

01:12:55.240 --> 01:12:59.720
And at the time, and some of them individually, they had done certain things in the civil

01:12:59.720 --> 01:13:04.440
rights movement, particularly some of them had gone north to Chester, Pennsylvania right

01:13:04.440 --> 01:13:09.400
outside of Philadelphia and been active in community work there.

01:13:09.400 --> 01:13:15.960
But anyway, SDS had started these economic research and action project to actually do

01:13:15.960 --> 01:13:16.960
work in the field.

01:13:16.960 --> 01:13:17.960
And the model was sick.

01:13:17.960 --> 01:13:22.560
And they were going to try to do what they call the interracial movement of the poor.

01:13:22.560 --> 01:13:33.000
And places in Chicago, Cleveland, Boston, and I'm probably missing someplace.

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:36.400
Yeah, Baltimore joined in Baltimore.

01:13:36.400 --> 01:13:42.320
And so I went to a party and ran to Tom Hayden.

01:13:42.320 --> 01:13:44.320
And he's got the talking.

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:47.120
I always say he got me drunk.

01:13:47.120 --> 01:13:50.640
And so he said, when did you come out of the door?

01:13:50.640 --> 01:13:51.640
See what we're doing.

01:13:51.640 --> 01:13:53.160
It's a lot like SNCC.

01:13:53.160 --> 01:13:57.120
And hey, you know, you're from the north.

01:13:57.120 --> 01:13:59.600
You probably can help us out on some stuff.

01:13:59.600 --> 01:14:05.640
So probably with the liquor and still in this post-Atlantic City thing.

01:14:05.640 --> 01:14:07.360
And I knew I was going to do the thing with Kennedy.

01:14:07.360 --> 01:14:11.160
I mean, he became a senator and that was good at the time.

01:14:11.160 --> 01:14:15.400
But I had no dreams of wanting to go to Washington and do that.

01:14:15.400 --> 01:14:18.760
So I said, let's go to check out Newark.

01:14:18.760 --> 01:14:22.800
And it was appealing because they, at the time, are talking about a statewide movement.

01:14:22.800 --> 01:14:27.680
And the idea that in terms of the 60 census, New Jersey was at that time the most, I don't

01:14:27.680 --> 01:14:31.720
know it, still maybe, but that was the most urbanized state in the country.

01:14:31.720 --> 01:14:37.160
So the idea was to start at Newark and Hoboken.

01:14:37.160 --> 01:14:39.640
And they had a project at Hoboken when at Newark.

01:14:39.640 --> 01:14:43.120
And we talked about doing something in the Elizabeth.

01:14:43.120 --> 01:14:45.520
And then maybe working down to Trenton.

01:14:45.520 --> 01:14:50.440
And there were some university people at New Brunswick and also at Princeton that, in terms

01:14:50.440 --> 01:14:53.880
of the academic level and research would be helpful.

01:14:53.880 --> 01:14:56.240
And so it was like a statewide movement.

01:14:56.240 --> 01:14:59.840
It wasn't just like going to one city, even though you were technically in one city.

01:14:59.840 --> 01:15:01.520
But the idea was going to there.

01:15:01.520 --> 01:15:03.600
And so that was appealing.

01:15:03.600 --> 01:15:08.040
And then the Jersey Turnpike, you can just connect really easily from city to city,

01:15:08.040 --> 01:15:11.640
place to place, which you couldn't do in Mississippi so easily.

01:15:11.640 --> 01:15:13.240
So that was attractive.

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:17.040
And so I'd always wanted to be in the North and do stuff.

01:15:17.040 --> 01:15:24.520
I had this little quote that the success of the anti-Jim Crow would be to turn Birmingham

01:15:24.520 --> 01:15:26.640
into Chicago.

01:15:26.640 --> 01:15:32.760
And places like Atlanta would become like New York.

01:15:32.760 --> 01:15:39.000
And so we would be facing the real problems of this country in a way that segregation,

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:41.880
racial segregation, had not allowed it to happen.

01:15:41.880 --> 01:15:46.440
And so this great victories that we were getting and which were hard fought and well earned

01:15:46.440 --> 01:15:50.440
and well deserved, were basically just putting us into the situation where we were like

01:15:50.440 --> 01:15:51.960
everybody else.

01:15:51.960 --> 01:15:56.200
And what's the America in that greater country economically, politically, and for freedom?

01:15:56.200 --> 01:16:00.520
And so that had always been my focus about why you had to work in the North.

01:16:00.520 --> 01:16:03.920
And so Newark opened that possibility.

01:16:03.920 --> 01:16:09.360
And SDS had a project and they actually, most of their organizers were white.

01:16:09.360 --> 01:16:12.760
They had a couple of black organizers.

01:16:12.760 --> 01:16:15.160
That was the part of it.

01:16:15.160 --> 01:16:17.120
I did not get to claim false labeling.

01:16:17.120 --> 01:16:18.200
I mean, we got there.

01:16:18.200 --> 01:16:20.000
There was no interracial movement of the poor.

01:16:20.000 --> 01:16:23.000
There were no white people who wanted to work with us.

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:25.760
We were Stanley Oranoids and other people.

01:16:25.760 --> 01:16:31.440
I did all these surveys on unemployment and particularly focused on New Jersey.

01:16:31.440 --> 01:16:33.520
And that was, and we thought we were going to work around unemployment.

01:16:33.520 --> 01:16:35.320
Well, that was not the issue people wanted to work on.

01:16:35.320 --> 01:16:40.600
They wanted to work around housing and rent and police brutality and things like that,

01:16:40.600 --> 01:16:42.840
which is what, you know, you do what the folks want to do.

01:16:42.840 --> 01:16:46.280
You're organizing it or you don't have a real project.

01:16:46.280 --> 01:16:47.280
So we ended up doing that.

01:16:47.280 --> 01:16:50.800
And it was mostly, you know, a black community.

01:16:50.800 --> 01:16:58.400
And we broke with the kind of more liberal group, the Clinton Hill neighborhood association.

01:16:58.400 --> 01:17:01.120
Got to name Stanley Winters, was head of that.

01:17:01.120 --> 01:17:07.040
And they had a very limited, kind of very, just generally at the time liberal.

01:17:07.040 --> 01:17:10.360
And we wanted to do more than that and raise basic questions.

01:17:10.360 --> 01:17:15.800
And so we broke off in the local, what was called the lower, hit the Clinton Hill section.

01:17:15.800 --> 01:17:18.520
And became a real power base.

01:17:18.520 --> 01:17:25.740
And then eventually, a year later, we'd start doing stuff in the central ward of New

01:17:25.740 --> 01:17:34.760
work, which was even more black and more poor and kind of the cesspool of New work.

01:17:34.760 --> 01:17:41.520
And I remember being with Tom Hayden in 65 during the Watts rebellion.

01:17:41.520 --> 01:17:45.680
And we were sitting there talking, looking at TV and saying, what is this is going to

01:17:45.680 --> 01:17:49.440
happen in New Jersey, in Newark.

01:17:49.440 --> 01:17:56.960
And more importantly, what would that impact be on us, what should we be doing, and so

01:17:56.960 --> 01:17:57.960
on.

01:17:57.960 --> 01:18:02.680
And so we, out of that conversation, then bringing other people into it, we developed

01:18:02.680 --> 01:18:08.560
a strategy for the next what became, we didn't know when, the next two years, so that when

01:18:08.560 --> 01:18:13.080
the Newark rebellion actually happened, you know, we had a game plan and an organizing

01:18:13.080 --> 01:18:16.960
thing of how to work on this.

01:18:16.960 --> 01:18:22.560
And it was basically as the move, but this was going into the mid 60s, becoming more racial

01:18:22.560 --> 01:18:29.840
conscious and the more black focus is we end to put issues in more racial terms.

01:18:29.840 --> 01:18:37.240
And since Newark was predominantly black at that time, still is today, and the people

01:18:37.240 --> 01:18:41.640
who were poor in destitute were also poor blacks.

01:18:41.640 --> 01:18:46.200
But the power structure, in this case, unlike Cleveland, which was Irish, were Italians.

01:18:46.200 --> 01:18:51.880
And as we began to pose that, like Newark was kind of many, this was one of the third

01:18:51.880 --> 01:18:54.480
role concepts we're heavy and people.

01:18:54.480 --> 01:19:03.240
So we were like a colonial African nation, struggling against these white European, Italian,

01:19:03.240 --> 01:19:06.720
American colonialists to get our liberation.

01:19:06.720 --> 01:19:10.080
I mean, quite say it that way, but that was the general thought.

01:19:10.080 --> 01:19:15.320
And so, as I mentioned in the bio, we were talking about black institutions and black

01:19:15.320 --> 01:19:20.080
power, community control, schools, neighborhoods, et cetera.

01:19:20.080 --> 01:19:23.400
We would get more black policemen.

01:19:23.400 --> 01:19:26.880
And I remember going through, you know, and this is what sort of, some of the class stuff

01:19:26.880 --> 01:19:31.640
gets in the involves too, because, well, why are you arguing for black policemen?

01:19:31.640 --> 01:19:36.400
And because police arrest people, they're agents of the state.

01:19:36.400 --> 01:19:41.280
And our answer was, which wasn't true in Mississippi, too, was, well, people have never seen

01:19:41.280 --> 01:19:43.120
black policemen.

01:19:43.120 --> 01:19:47.880
And until they actually see a black policeman, get up, get beat up by a black policeman,

01:19:47.880 --> 01:19:50.080
they won't get to see what police are really about.

01:19:50.080 --> 01:19:53.800
They're going to think it's really a white control thing.

01:19:53.800 --> 01:19:58.280
And so they have to get at the level through direct experience of seeing the system at

01:19:58.280 --> 01:20:00.120
work using black people.

01:20:00.120 --> 01:20:04.800
But if there are no black people at the higher ranks of the city of the system, which

01:20:04.800 --> 01:20:10.440
includes mayors and congresspeople as well, then I mean, this is where we get some of

01:20:10.440 --> 01:20:15.880
our left friends who just way out and left feel literally is that you can't talk about socialism

01:20:15.880 --> 01:20:20.760
or capitalism at a level when people are feeling the racial thing, you know, most heavy in

01:20:20.760 --> 01:20:22.400
their daily life.

01:20:22.400 --> 01:20:24.120
So I mean, that became some of the things.

01:20:24.120 --> 01:20:27.160
So we spent a lot of time polarizing.

01:20:27.160 --> 01:20:32.520
And what's interesting in terms of new experience for me looking back on it is we were, you know,

01:20:32.520 --> 01:20:34.200
we had some real power.

01:20:34.200 --> 01:20:37.560
I mean, the authorities really had, look, because we had a real grassroots base.

01:20:37.560 --> 01:20:42.040
And nothing I've worked with in the same way since has had that type of grassroots base,

01:20:42.040 --> 01:20:47.760
where the mayor and the city council, you know, were very, you know, concerned and leery

01:20:47.760 --> 01:20:52.320
what we were going to do, tried to bring in some of the old, but we called them, the uncle

01:20:52.320 --> 01:20:55.160
thoms who were the Negro politicians.

01:20:55.160 --> 01:21:01.080
And I mean, they literally broke our windows and slashed some of the tires of the people

01:21:01.080 --> 01:21:02.080
on the car.

01:21:02.080 --> 01:21:05.800
And one time we were in the middle of Springfield Lab, then we almost got a physical

01:21:05.800 --> 01:21:07.840
altercation with them.

01:21:07.840 --> 01:21:11.560
And I forget how that stopped, but it didn't actually happen.

01:21:11.560 --> 01:21:17.360
And the guy who was hit at the local Democratic Party and the central ward got him, Ulyss

01:21:17.360 --> 01:21:19.480
Honey Ward.

01:21:19.480 --> 01:21:22.480
Very good guy, but he was totally into the old framework.

01:21:22.480 --> 01:21:27.560
And he wasn't knock our blocks off because we were these new folks and all these white

01:21:27.560 --> 01:21:30.680
radicals from SDS, it really set us up to do this.

01:21:30.680 --> 01:21:31.680
And blah, blah, blah.

01:21:31.680 --> 01:21:35.640
I mean, you probably heard variations in the story.

01:21:35.640 --> 01:21:37.960
So it was very thrilling, you've disailyced.

01:21:37.960 --> 01:21:42.120
And we lived in the community.

01:21:42.120 --> 01:21:43.840
I stayed.

01:21:43.840 --> 01:21:45.320
We didn't have a project house at one time.

01:21:45.320 --> 01:21:46.840
We got a little bit more money.

01:21:46.840 --> 01:21:50.760
We got most of our money from Weber unions.

01:21:50.760 --> 01:21:54.160
And probably, I know the UWA gave us some money.

01:21:54.480 --> 01:21:57.960
There was another union, which I can't remember that would give us some money.

01:21:57.960 --> 01:22:03.080
And some church money, mostly from the Episcopal Pallion Church, which is how I got in contact

01:22:03.080 --> 01:22:05.600
with Nathan Wright.

01:22:05.600 --> 01:22:12.960
And he would write a book on Black Power and Newark, but more importantly, he was the

01:22:12.960 --> 01:22:19.800
organizer for the first Black Power Conference right after the Newark Rebellion.

01:22:19.800 --> 01:22:21.280
And he didn't have that grass roots thing.

01:22:21.280 --> 01:22:24.120
That's how that was my role to come in and do that.

01:22:24.120 --> 01:22:27.640
But he had other kinds of ties, which I didn't have.

01:22:27.640 --> 01:22:31.280
And so that was useful.

01:22:31.280 --> 01:22:44.080
Let me ask how you're bridging between SDS and Central Ward, which isn't basically entirely

01:22:44.080 --> 01:22:45.080
black.

01:22:45.080 --> 01:22:51.480
How are you managing between pre-managing the race and class question simultaneously,

01:22:51.480 --> 01:22:53.280
organizational sense?

01:22:53.280 --> 01:22:59.880
Well, in terms of what we call NCOP, Newark Community Union Project, which was an SDS-oriented

01:22:59.880 --> 01:23:06.800
organized project, is that pretty much entirely organized by SDS.

01:23:06.800 --> 01:23:10.680
Most of their work was pretty much all their work, except with them, has been in the South

01:23:10.680 --> 01:23:16.040
Ward, except with some of the little forerays that mostly Tom had done, Tom Hayden, had

01:23:16.040 --> 01:23:17.640
done an essential award.

01:23:17.640 --> 01:23:20.880
And we'd done that together.

01:23:20.880 --> 01:23:29.720
But at a certain point by 65, I think some of the white folks were realizing the limitations

01:23:29.720 --> 01:23:34.320
of white organizing in a predominantly black community in a way that had not really been

01:23:34.320 --> 01:23:40.240
raised quite as heavily in the early 60s, or even when the project first started.

01:23:40.240 --> 01:23:47.520
And since the idea of the interracial movement of the port was not happening, it wasn't

01:23:47.520 --> 01:23:52.640
like they could go to white folks and offer the hand of unity and bridging the gap and all

01:23:52.640 --> 01:23:53.640
of that.

01:23:53.640 --> 01:24:01.380
So some of them began to play more technical roles, fundraising, doing research on city

01:24:01.380 --> 01:24:06.080
structures, which was totally useful, because frontline organizers never have time in any

01:24:06.080 --> 01:24:08.560
struggle to do that kind of stuff.

01:24:08.560 --> 01:24:14.680
Working ties with some of the university people, but playing of that's a visible role.

01:24:14.680 --> 01:24:15.680
They also got race-baited.

01:24:15.680 --> 01:24:23.960
I mean, Leroy Jones, who was his home base for where he'd grown up, and he had formed

01:24:23.960 --> 01:24:33.480
his group called the Spirit House, actually got a race-baited, not kind of he did.

01:24:33.480 --> 01:24:36.720
And I know sometimes the meetings he would ask me, well, who are you representing these

01:24:36.720 --> 01:24:41.320
white folks, or are you representing, are you with us?

01:24:41.320 --> 01:24:45.720
And I said, we say, I'm representing people that I'm organizing in the Central Ward, who

01:24:45.720 --> 01:24:49.440
were like 99% black.

01:24:49.440 --> 01:24:51.800
And also we got allies.

01:24:51.800 --> 01:24:58.560
One guy was a guy named Willie Wright, who became, oh, she'd say, one of the things that

01:24:58.560 --> 01:25:03.960
happened in somewhere, I guess, between 64 and 64 is this thing called the poverty program,

01:25:03.960 --> 01:25:05.760
anti-apomany program.

01:25:05.760 --> 01:25:10.520
And because there was a national program everywhere and had money and resources, we had to figure

01:25:10.520 --> 01:25:12.760
out how to do with it.

01:25:12.760 --> 01:25:19.720
Yeah, so we had to figure out whether we should ignore it and some of the things like the

01:25:19.720 --> 01:25:25.160
VISTA program, which would bring in young, predominantly white kids into some of the same

01:25:25.160 --> 01:25:30.200
areas that we were working in, or should we try to take it over.

01:25:30.200 --> 01:25:34.720
So after some major discussions, we had a similar debate on this around the Democratic

01:25:34.720 --> 01:25:35.720
Party, by the way.

01:25:35.720 --> 01:25:38.920
There was something called the United Freedom Party, which is like a third party was led

01:25:38.920 --> 01:25:43.920
by a guy named George Richardson, who had been a former state assemblyman with a Democrat,

01:25:43.920 --> 01:25:46.320
and had broken with the Democratic boss.

01:25:46.320 --> 01:25:52.900
And as a way to threaten him, the boss, that is, he formed the third line so that the

01:25:52.900 --> 01:25:58.040
Republicans could seevably win if they withheld a significant vote.

01:25:58.040 --> 01:26:02.960
So that was a prior discussion that had gotten us thinking about that kind of strategy.

01:26:02.960 --> 01:26:07.480
But we decided not to do that in the case of the federal government, and we decided

01:26:07.480 --> 01:26:09.920
that's what we have a community base.

01:26:09.920 --> 01:26:14.200
Let's become the poverty program, because the feds can't do that.

01:26:14.200 --> 01:26:22.200
So we basically, what was called District 3, which is a South Ward, we literally had

01:26:22.200 --> 01:26:24.840
the forces to take over the poverty.

01:26:24.840 --> 01:26:31.240
We hired one of our own people as the staff organizer, got named Jesse Allen, and Bessie

01:26:31.240 --> 01:26:37.320
Smith, who was our version of Fannie Lou Hamer, was the chairperson, not paid, Jesse was

01:26:37.320 --> 01:26:40.240
paid of the board.

01:26:40.240 --> 01:26:47.720
We had quarters where the government office at that poverty program in the third ward.

01:26:47.720 --> 01:26:52.600
In the central ward, we didn't quite have, we hadn't spent as much time developing

01:26:52.600 --> 01:26:53.600
base.

01:26:53.600 --> 01:26:57.720
So we had some base, and we were able to work with a guy who was kind of like a local black

01:26:57.720 --> 01:27:01.480
nationalist, and they didn't really write.

01:27:01.480 --> 01:27:07.280
And he almost, when he gave speeches, he kind of reminded you of Malcolm X a little bit.

01:27:07.280 --> 01:27:11.680
But, you know, we were, what tied us together, we were both insurgent forces.

01:27:11.680 --> 01:27:17.080
So we got him elected to be the chairman of the area board too.

01:27:17.080 --> 01:27:24.160
So we essentially controlled two boards in the two most poverty-stricken areas of Newark.

01:27:24.160 --> 01:27:28.560
And so we were a serious force, you know, to be dealt with.

01:27:28.560 --> 01:27:33.240
So there were some downsides, I mean, and to that, what is that?

01:27:33.240 --> 01:27:39.640
In the focus of the government, in the government large, yes, we lost a little bit of the community.

01:27:39.640 --> 01:27:45.000
Not so much in terms of actual people, but being able to have that, I mean, before the

01:27:45.000 --> 01:27:50.840
government, we spent like 90% of our time in the community on the day, and during the

01:27:50.840 --> 01:27:51.840
day.

01:27:51.840 --> 01:27:57.560
In fact, the folks of these nonprofits now who go out and I even belong to a couple,

01:27:57.560 --> 01:28:02.120
it's a big thing for them to go out to their community once a week and for a couple

01:28:02.120 --> 01:28:03.120
of hours.

01:28:03.120 --> 01:28:08.640
And we were there six days a week and more frequent on the weekends, I'd take advantage

01:28:08.640 --> 01:28:14.600
of the closest of New York and take the subway, the path over to spend time in New York,

01:28:14.600 --> 01:28:18.120
saying, hang, get out of it for a minute and come back.

01:28:18.120 --> 01:28:19.800
But we were there.

01:28:19.800 --> 01:28:25.960
But we lost that because what happened is that we had these fancy phones with push buttons

01:28:25.960 --> 01:28:30.560
and Jesse, who was the organizer and Dolvin Higgins, who was another sub organizer.

01:28:30.560 --> 01:28:34.000
They could just spend all their time in their office and didn't have to go out in the

01:28:34.000 --> 01:28:35.280
community and knock on doors anymore.

01:28:35.280 --> 01:28:40.880
It's like, you come to us and we had these nice couches, leather couches that were said,

01:28:40.880 --> 01:28:48.480
where before people had donated their own couches to our neighborhood storefront office.

01:28:48.480 --> 01:28:53.200
So there was a sense of ownership at the community level that they had.

01:28:53.200 --> 01:28:57.400
They had put up money or they had put up their furniture.

01:28:57.400 --> 01:29:02.040
We had meals together, which we had paid for and we shared.

01:29:02.040 --> 01:29:05.440
And we were poor, but we shared and we made do.

01:29:05.440 --> 01:29:11.680
All of a sudden now we have nice big meeting halls and phones and come down to my office.

01:29:11.680 --> 01:29:15.040
I don't have time to talk to five different people.

01:29:15.040 --> 01:29:16.200
I don't have time to do that.

01:29:16.200 --> 01:29:18.200
I'm saying the most provocative way.

01:29:18.200 --> 01:29:20.440
It wasn't quite felt that way all the time.

01:29:20.440 --> 01:29:27.280
But that's why I say we lost a little bit of the community or the community feel of

01:29:27.280 --> 01:29:28.760
in the poverty program.

01:29:28.760 --> 01:29:36.320
But for 64, you know, that little famous clause, the maximum feasible possession of the

01:29:36.320 --> 01:29:40.120
poor, we worked it to the bone.

01:29:40.120 --> 01:29:48.360
And in fact, one time a new director of the, it was called the United Community Corporation.

01:29:48.360 --> 01:29:51.720
You see that was the official name of the poverty program in Newark.

01:29:51.720 --> 01:29:57.360
They had a new director come in from the urban league and he would later come to Cleveland.

01:29:57.360 --> 01:29:59.320
That's kind of interesting.

01:29:59.320 --> 01:30:01.640
But the community wanted to have some buttons.

01:30:01.640 --> 01:30:04.440
So they wanted to have their community action director.

01:30:04.440 --> 01:30:08.280
And so they nominated me to be the community action director.

01:30:08.280 --> 01:30:11.320
And of course, the top folks didn't want that.

01:30:11.320 --> 01:30:13.120
So I didn't get the position.

01:30:13.120 --> 01:30:18.060
And I remember looking at it in hindsight, there was a salary of $12,000, which was big time

01:30:18.060 --> 01:30:19.060
money.

01:30:19.060 --> 01:30:22.520
I never got $12,000 in my life.

01:30:22.520 --> 01:30:26.520
So a small part, I was like, hey, I wouldn't become rich in this job.

01:30:26.520 --> 01:30:32.520
And because we were kind of living hand to foot at the level of, that's my joke by the way

01:30:32.520 --> 01:30:33.520
now.

01:30:34.520 --> 01:30:37.520
I can tell you politically how I got through the 60s.

01:30:37.520 --> 01:30:42.240
But if you had to ask me economically how I managed to get through the 60s, I could be

01:30:42.240 --> 01:30:45.000
down in Guantanamo and being tortured.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:49.840
And I could not give you a yearly account or a monthly account for all those years of

01:30:49.840 --> 01:30:50.840
how I survived.

01:30:50.840 --> 01:30:53.440
You'd have to torture me and I couldn't do it.

01:30:53.440 --> 01:30:57.960
Because having, that's, I mean, it was a whole different climate.

01:30:57.960 --> 01:31:03.440
Sharing, sleeping on people's sofas and community folks letting us stay in the house.

01:31:03.440 --> 01:31:07.480
I used to have this very elaborate system of where I was getting meals.

01:31:07.480 --> 01:31:10.640
And so I'd say, okay, Joe, I actually went down.

01:31:10.640 --> 01:31:15.480
So the first Monday and the third Tuesday of each month, I'm going to come over your

01:31:15.480 --> 01:31:16.480
house.

01:31:16.480 --> 01:31:18.680
I'm just going to happen to drop by at dinner time.

01:31:18.680 --> 01:31:20.680
And because you saw me in the community, you say, hey, I'm full.

01:31:20.680 --> 01:31:21.680
Stay for dinner.

01:31:21.680 --> 01:31:22.680
Okay.

01:31:22.680 --> 01:31:28.680
You, I'm going to come all the third Wednesday and the fifth month of the month.

01:31:28.680 --> 01:31:32.200
And I do my whole couple of blocks that I was kind of liaison for.

01:31:32.200 --> 01:31:34.320
So it would look spontaneous.

01:31:34.320 --> 01:31:38.400
But it would be very planned and I would know I'd have meals.

01:31:38.400 --> 01:31:39.600
Because I'd bring news.

01:31:39.600 --> 01:31:43.640
And so I was always, it's like that famous commercial I was used to love about the guy

01:31:43.640 --> 01:31:47.120
who goes camping and all he takes to the six pack of blood wiser.

01:31:47.120 --> 01:31:50.560
And everybody comes and greets them and takes them and takes good care of them.

01:31:50.560 --> 01:31:51.560
I mean, I brought the news.

01:31:51.560 --> 01:31:57.140
I could tell you what your neighbor was doing, what the landlord was doing, what the

01:31:57.140 --> 01:32:02.580
electric company was, who was fussing with that or the church meeting here.

01:32:02.580 --> 01:32:04.860
And so I was in some ways a welcome guest.

01:32:04.860 --> 01:32:07.380
I mean, he was partly organizing.

01:32:07.380 --> 01:32:08.780
And I could be part of the social thing.

01:32:08.780 --> 01:32:17.140
I was telling somebody here that what, as part of the Explore, one of the central ward neighborhoods,

01:32:17.140 --> 01:32:21.700
I went into this bar and they said, I was looking to see what was happening and going

01:32:21.700 --> 01:32:23.620
on and I was new.

01:32:23.620 --> 01:32:28.940
And so I saw something on the bar and said, Christian bothers meet from two to three every Sunday.

01:32:28.940 --> 01:32:32.420
I said, oh, that's a good, I'm going to check out with.

01:32:32.420 --> 01:32:37.220
And so I asked him, and Barthand I said, what does this Christian brothers group do in

01:32:37.220 --> 01:32:38.220
their meetings?

01:32:38.220 --> 01:32:41.500
And he got to be kind of the way you, you're just looking at that.

01:32:41.500 --> 01:32:45.580
Oh, we just drink Christian brothers liquor.

01:32:45.580 --> 01:32:49.780
Here I said it was going to be a social group and make connections.

01:32:49.780 --> 01:32:51.580
So I had a lot of great stories like that.

01:32:51.580 --> 01:32:54.300
And that's what made it interesting and learning at the same time.

01:32:54.300 --> 01:32:55.500
And you felt you were in the public.

01:32:55.500 --> 01:32:56.500
Yeah.

01:32:56.500 --> 01:33:00.500
I mean, I said we had a face in the city.

01:33:00.500 --> 01:33:05.500
And so I mean, after the rebellion, folks wanted to blame the riot on us and to say the

01:33:05.500 --> 01:33:06.500
agree.

01:33:06.500 --> 01:33:10.700
Yeah, before we get to that, would the mayor of Newark have known who you are in this

01:33:10.700 --> 01:33:11.700
year?

01:33:11.700 --> 01:33:16.420
I don't know.

01:33:16.420 --> 01:33:18.780
Some of his people would have.

01:33:18.780 --> 01:33:24.620
He had a guy named Donald Melafronte, who I can't remember his exact title, but he was

01:33:24.620 --> 01:33:26.860
like chief of staff.

01:33:26.860 --> 01:33:32.300
And I decided, because he was at every community meeting running down the garbage from the mayor's

01:33:32.300 --> 01:33:33.300
office.

01:33:33.300 --> 01:33:38.180
So I personally decided to make him the arch bad guy.

01:33:38.180 --> 01:33:43.700
And so anytime I had a chance, publicly or privately, I actually would have called him.

01:33:43.700 --> 01:33:48.300
There was a guy named White Guy, an interesting guy who's dead, unfortunately, named Derek

01:33:48.300 --> 01:33:49.300
Wyden's.

01:33:49.300 --> 01:33:53.700
He came from a fairly wealthy family in New Jersey.

01:33:53.700 --> 01:33:56.220
I can't remember exactly what their money was from.

01:33:56.220 --> 01:33:58.540
But Derek got interested in the movement.

01:33:58.540 --> 01:34:04.220
And since hometown, he saw us and some of the people we were close to being the real

01:34:04.220 --> 01:34:06.740
progressive force of the future.

01:34:06.740 --> 01:34:09.860
And so he did all kinds of things to help us.

01:34:09.860 --> 01:34:14.540
So one of the things he did, he said a newspaper, a community newspaper called The Newark

01:34:14.540 --> 01:34:15.700
Advance.

01:34:15.700 --> 01:34:16.700
And I wrote a column.

01:34:16.700 --> 01:34:21.020
And I think I came out every two weeks or something like that.

01:34:21.020 --> 01:34:26.500
And so usually I find somebody in the column that talk about Donald Melafronte and as the

01:34:26.500 --> 01:34:29.820
arch bad guy of everything.

01:34:29.820 --> 01:34:32.620
And so he would know who I was.

01:34:32.620 --> 01:34:37.140
And then some of the really good guy named Doug Edwards, who wrote for the Newark Star

01:34:37.140 --> 01:34:38.140
Ledger.

01:34:38.140 --> 01:34:41.220
And he covered a lot of our stuff.

01:34:41.220 --> 01:34:45.380
And I don't know if he's still alive or if he's passed out.

01:34:45.380 --> 01:34:51.980
So we were picking our friends on enemies mainly because we were a force beyond the neighborhood.

01:34:51.980 --> 01:34:56.940
If we were just in the neighborhood, folks downtown wouldn't have cared that much.

01:34:56.940 --> 01:35:03.180
But because we had a much bigger view, we were making ties, connections on the West Ward,

01:35:03.180 --> 01:35:06.980
which by 67 we had really kind of real basin.

01:35:06.980 --> 01:35:11.300
But I mean people were aware of us as a force in the town.

01:35:11.300 --> 01:35:13.540
And that's why I say I've never been anything quite like that since.

01:35:13.540 --> 01:35:20.540
Whether Detroit or here where he had that access to some degree of cloud.

01:35:20.540 --> 01:35:25.620
How are you managing say 65, 66 with?

01:35:25.620 --> 01:35:31.220
Would you formally describe yourself still then after you're sort of deeply in the Newark

01:35:31.220 --> 01:35:33.900
experience as a member of SNCC?

01:35:33.900 --> 01:35:34.900
Well no.

01:35:34.900 --> 01:35:40.300
I mean some of it's personality, some of it's politics, some it's cross.

01:35:40.300 --> 01:35:46.180
It's really the energy that's happening with the times.

01:35:46.180 --> 01:35:52.060
So like I moved to December, Newark in December thanks to Tom Hayden and the party and all

01:35:52.060 --> 01:35:54.220
that.

01:35:54.220 --> 01:35:58.620
And was bringing in the work with in cup again doing community work.

01:35:58.620 --> 01:36:03.500
And all of a sudden SDS decided that they wanted to do this March in Washington.

01:36:03.500 --> 01:36:06.620
It would become the first major march against the war in Vietnam.

01:36:06.620 --> 01:36:10.780
In April, I think I want to say 19th, 1965.

01:36:10.780 --> 01:36:11.780
I think.

01:36:11.780 --> 01:36:18.060
But anyway, in April, 1965 Paul Booth was the national chair of SDS the time was the main

01:36:18.060 --> 01:36:21.900
speaker and his great speech was we have to name the system.

01:36:21.900 --> 01:36:23.380
You know, just that protest.

01:36:23.380 --> 01:36:27.420
But anyway, but the problem is SDS didn't have any real basin DC.

01:36:27.420 --> 01:36:34.300
And so I remember they came up to Newark and asked if I could be released to go back to

01:36:34.300 --> 01:36:43.340
Washington where I got new people and be one of the organizers for the March.

01:36:43.340 --> 01:36:49.900
And which I said to the SDS people, I mean to the Iraq people in cup, you know, it was

01:36:49.900 --> 01:36:50.900
up to them.

01:36:50.900 --> 01:36:55.580
And they said, yeah, this is important because there's a big work we're doing in Newark.

01:36:55.580 --> 01:37:00.980
We think it's important, but there's also a world which we have to have an awareness of.

01:37:00.980 --> 01:37:07.800
And if you have some skills in DC and can do some of this, so the lead organizer from

01:37:07.800 --> 01:37:13.660
SDS was a guy named Paul Booth, who I think at the time was the national vice president.

01:37:13.660 --> 01:37:19.060
And he was there and I was the main organizer.

01:37:19.060 --> 01:37:22.980
And in some ways I had done something a little different, but similar in 63 with the March

01:37:22.980 --> 01:37:24.740
and Washington committee.

01:37:24.740 --> 01:37:30.140
And you had Byred Rustin, who again was one of our mentors, who was basically organizing

01:37:30.140 --> 01:37:35.180
the National March and Washington somewhere along the line, they realized they had forgotten

01:37:35.180 --> 01:37:37.260
about DC.

01:37:37.260 --> 01:37:40.780
And we're bringing all these people from all over the country and nobody has tried to do

01:37:40.780 --> 01:37:44.140
anything about mobilizing Washington DC, the people there.

01:37:44.140 --> 01:37:46.860
And they're going to feel totally invaded.

01:37:46.860 --> 01:37:48.300
And what is this and all that.

01:37:48.300 --> 01:37:56.100
So he leaned on some of the NAD kids as we were called and to actually do some, so we

01:37:56.100 --> 01:38:02.420
formed a little group and he said we will basically be the organizers for Gideon Cleveland

01:38:02.420 --> 01:38:09.260
Robinson, who was one of the more national folks in the March and Washington gave us money,

01:38:09.260 --> 01:38:12.220
oh, she'd say, God, us money didn't give it to us personally, I was pocket.

01:38:12.220 --> 01:38:16.540
But you got some money to set up an office.

01:38:16.540 --> 01:38:22.300
And then later a couple of deaths in the main office so we could have coronation and

01:38:22.300 --> 01:38:26.340
Norman Hill from court, Congress, racial equality was part of that.

01:38:26.340 --> 01:38:27.980
I say him because he was our generation.

01:38:27.980 --> 01:38:32.020
He was one of the younger upcoming people in court at that time.

01:38:32.020 --> 01:38:35.620
And we basically organized in DC.

01:38:35.620 --> 01:38:38.540
Cleveland Robinson went to the unions in DC.

01:38:38.540 --> 01:38:42.820
We went to a lot of churches, community groups, so that we could get a turnout.

01:38:42.820 --> 01:38:49.340
But also people, we got places for people to stay, who were coming not just for the day

01:38:49.340 --> 01:38:51.220
from other places.

01:38:51.220 --> 01:38:55.060
Churches opened up so people could go and get food and clothing.

01:38:55.060 --> 01:39:01.860
Not so much clothing, but food and water and respite, missments for a while.

01:39:01.860 --> 01:39:06.660
So again it was just having gone to college and done some work in DC that made that possible

01:39:06.660 --> 01:39:11.100
in 63 and then also in 65 now with the anti-war thing.

01:39:11.100 --> 01:39:12.620
Then after that I went right back to Newark.

01:39:12.620 --> 01:39:13.620
Yeah.

01:39:13.620 --> 01:39:22.540
So in terms of the SDS stick thing, I think some of the SDS people were moving more consciously

01:39:22.540 --> 01:39:30.900
to the anti-Vietnam War thing in real, in some degree in relationship to the more black,

01:39:30.900 --> 01:39:34.420
nationalist tone around organizing in urban communities.

01:39:34.420 --> 01:39:37.180
It wasn't necessarily a boom, boom thing.

01:39:37.180 --> 01:39:40.940
It was gradual and some people stayed like Tom stayed for a long time.

01:39:40.940 --> 01:39:46.060
But then Tom went to Vietnam with Herbert Abducker and Staten Linh.

01:39:46.060 --> 01:39:49.940
Then he came back to Newark and talked about what it was like to be in Vietnam and he

01:39:49.940 --> 01:39:55.820
was able to humanize both Vietnam and the Vietnamese in a way that never would have been possible

01:39:55.820 --> 01:40:01.020
if somebody had that we knew, you know, had gone to Vietnam.

01:40:01.020 --> 01:40:02.020
But that was that shift.

01:40:02.020 --> 01:40:06.620
And so what happened with me personally is this goes back to Nag, is that when Stokley

01:40:06.620 --> 01:40:11.220
becomes chair of SNCC and wants to take you in a different direction, I remember he

01:40:11.220 --> 01:40:16.020
comes up to Newark, we talk and he says you want to be part of this new action.

01:40:16.020 --> 01:40:18.900
And I said this sounds cool.

01:40:18.900 --> 01:40:24.980
And at the time also it allowed me to think about a different kind of focus for the

01:40:24.980 --> 01:40:28.900
Central Ward which was more around the black power as opposed to just the black and white

01:40:28.900 --> 01:40:31.100
thing.

01:40:31.100 --> 01:40:34.660
And which in terms of people's real life experience they didn't see that happening.

01:40:34.660 --> 01:40:36.660
So it was a theoretical construct.

01:40:36.660 --> 01:40:41.060
Let me get you right at that moment and say when Stokley comes to have this conversation

01:40:41.060 --> 01:40:49.020
with you, he's the spring of 1966 I guess when he asked John Lewis that.

01:40:49.020 --> 01:40:53.500
John still says a matter about that too.

01:40:53.500 --> 01:41:04.420
Tell me about how you would have, in some basic summary fashion, you describe the vision

01:41:04.420 --> 01:41:09.500
of the perspective you had, the way you added up what you were trying to do and what

01:41:09.500 --> 01:41:13.700
your critique was and how you wanted to get where you wanted to go.

01:41:13.700 --> 01:41:14.700
In Newarker in general?

01:41:14.700 --> 01:41:15.700
In general.

01:41:15.700 --> 01:41:20.980
Your philosophy about how to do what you wanted to do.

01:41:20.980 --> 01:41:25.660
Well I think coming up both starting with SNCC and then the experience in Newark with

01:41:25.660 --> 01:41:32.460
SDS is we felt that the true bearers of future change were going to be the grassroots

01:41:32.460 --> 01:41:39.020
communities, poor people, even poor white people that we were running into and organizing

01:41:39.020 --> 01:41:40.020
in certain places.

01:41:40.020 --> 01:41:44.020
And so we were afforded in some ways doing the prototype of what would be the future

01:41:44.020 --> 01:41:45.020
society.

01:41:45.020 --> 01:41:49.020
There were going to be room for a lot of allies and the church, the labor unions, research

01:41:49.020 --> 01:41:50.660
and teachers so.

01:41:50.660 --> 01:41:54.800
But in terms of where the force of that change was going to come from, was people who had

01:41:54.800 --> 01:42:03.040
gotten the least and had the least stake in maintaining the current setup of the way

01:42:03.040 --> 01:42:05.440
government and the society was set up.

01:42:05.440 --> 01:42:11.480
So we felt that what SNCC was doing and what SDS was doing emphasized that and that as

01:42:11.480 --> 01:42:17.920
the racial dynamic as was getting to spread around the country, thanks to the urban rebellions

01:42:17.920 --> 01:42:19.760
all around the country.

01:42:19.760 --> 01:42:25.240
And we were experiencing something which we had no real answer for in terms of our southern

01:42:25.240 --> 01:42:26.240
experience.

01:42:26.240 --> 01:42:30.320
And I was true with Martin Luther King with the Chicago, he did the same thing happen.

01:42:30.320 --> 01:42:34.680
Both at the level of the violence but also at the level of the Democratic Party because

01:42:34.680 --> 01:42:41.240
our whole objective in the South had been to get into something that was keeping us out.

01:42:41.240 --> 01:42:46.480
So when Martin King gets to Chicago, Mary daily says come on in, become a Democrat and

01:42:46.480 --> 01:42:47.480
join the party.

01:42:47.480 --> 01:42:51.560
Of course you're going to be at the bottom and I mean your key authorities, well the

01:42:51.560 --> 01:42:54.960
first is all we'll make a symbolic position for you but everybody else is going to come

01:42:54.960 --> 01:43:01.720
in at the bottom level and we'll just replay the society with new forms now.

01:43:01.720 --> 01:43:07.000
And the civil rights movement, the traditional southern base civil rights movement had no

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:08.400
answer for that either.

01:43:08.400 --> 01:43:15.640
So both at the level of the increasing violence, people not feeling a inherent to nonviolence

01:43:15.640 --> 01:43:23.880
as well as the fact that there was racism without segregation laws in the North, we didn't

01:43:23.880 --> 01:43:24.880
have an answer to that.

01:43:24.880 --> 01:43:30.600
So it was like we had to make up as we went along because there was no theoretical

01:43:30.600 --> 01:43:32.800
struggles for how that was going to happen.

01:43:32.800 --> 01:43:39.600
Would you see the elements that were essentially reformists and the elements were radical?

01:43:39.600 --> 01:43:40.600
Which?

01:43:40.600 --> 01:43:45.160
How would you have said in my program, these are essentially reformists and these are

01:43:45.160 --> 01:43:46.920
essentially radical?

01:43:46.920 --> 01:43:51.800
Well for the most part we were against the Democratic Party and because we felt the Democratic

01:43:51.800 --> 01:44:00.360
Party was sometimes people said the plantation which caught up and trapped all the, particularly

01:44:00.360 --> 01:44:06.400
that time, the black initiative that was trying to rise up and that in some ways it might

01:44:06.400 --> 01:44:11.600
be better than the sharecropper system of the South but it was still a bondied system

01:44:11.600 --> 01:44:19.360
and that the way people called the, whether it was Tamini Hall in New York or the Daily

01:44:19.360 --> 01:44:25.160
Machine in Chicago and variations of that around the country, they still made the rules.

01:44:25.160 --> 01:44:30.960
I mean it was the Democratic Party machine in Newark, the Italians and Irish as second

01:44:30.960 --> 01:44:35.160
classes and then we were at the very bottom and then there were few blacks who got into

01:44:35.240 --> 01:44:39.400
that was bottom level position but they were bottom level positions and most of us didn't

01:44:39.400 --> 01:44:44.840
get into it at all so that was not benefiting anybody that we were trying to organize and

01:44:44.840 --> 01:44:49.480
that we had to give people some sense that civic action in the old sense of that word,

01:44:49.480 --> 01:44:53.720
civic action could make a difference and it was not going to be through mainstream structures.

01:44:53.720 --> 01:45:02.360
I mean what about how you saw what your program was to sort of overleak that obstacle posed

01:45:02.440 --> 01:45:07.560
by the Democratic Party by that structural reality? Well as I said we went through again learning

01:45:07.560 --> 01:45:14.360
as we did so like in Newark, remember we made this temporary alliance with George Richardson,

01:45:14.920 --> 01:45:19.640
the former state's assemblyman to work in something called the United Freedom Party,

01:45:21.640 --> 01:45:28.120
UFP, United Freedom Party and that was experience, I mean it was a little bit beyond our scope

01:45:28.120 --> 01:45:35.880
because we were the involved, we were door knockers and people's issues around housing and welfare

01:45:35.880 --> 01:45:41.080
and not electoral politics because electoral politics was basically a field that was way beyond

01:45:41.080 --> 01:45:47.560
our control to and pretty much bringing me a group to actually control that and not just at

01:45:47.560 --> 01:45:54.600
a level of money but money being an important one as well and we were coming abreast at the time

01:45:54.600 --> 01:46:00.840
on television which it really got in terms of the early 60s but by the mid 60s people were

01:46:00.840 --> 01:46:05.640
saying things which are never were possible to do and having access to those things. I mean we

01:46:05.640 --> 01:46:10.760
were fortunate but in terms of the day that particularly in the black power period at any time

01:46:10.760 --> 01:46:16.600
we used to joke, you just put up here dark glasses and love a jacket and say boo and you're on page

01:46:16.600 --> 01:46:23.480
one, you especially have a big afro and that's no longer true for us, press learns too but sometimes

01:46:23.480 --> 01:46:29.720
you would use the other side or some of the apparatus on the other side to promote your cause

01:46:30.520 --> 01:46:35.560
and so that became one of the things that happened stick a little later which was unfortunate is

01:46:35.560 --> 01:46:41.400
that we frequently talk essentially what we used to call the white press to make announcements to

01:46:41.400 --> 01:46:47.560
black people would be us we didn't have our own institutions to be able to do that, you know

01:46:47.560 --> 01:46:51.560
it was a real problem that I mean it worked and it didn't work because then the press could do

01:46:51.880 --> 01:46:56.520
the interpretation they would carry us but then so frequently and this it was true particularly

01:46:56.520 --> 01:47:02.360
with Stokeley he would always say I miss being miss quoted and or be quoted out of context

01:47:02.920 --> 01:47:07.800
because that was they would carry him in the you know he'd be on front page or whatever

01:47:07.800 --> 01:47:13.880
but usually in a way that showed him as a wild man making all these volatile statements

01:47:13.880 --> 01:47:19.480
and no sense of you know context for that. When you took a remarkable came to in 66 with this

01:47:19.560 --> 01:47:26.120
proposal that you were mentioning but were you because of your history and time together back in

01:47:26.120 --> 01:47:31.640
nag and Howard would you have said you were you had a personal friendship that you were moving

01:47:31.640 --> 01:47:38.840
forward from or an alliance born of common struggle you know or different roles in the common

01:47:38.840 --> 01:47:43.960
struggle. Well some of both I mean I knew his family I know the mother I actually had a brief

01:47:43.960 --> 01:47:52.680
flirtation with his sister and visited his house in the Bronx and so I mean we weren't necessarily

01:47:52.680 --> 01:47:57.080
I wouldn't say that he was my best friend and I don't think he would ever say I was his best friend

01:47:57.080 --> 01:48:02.120
and we we challenged each other a lot of things I looked up to him totally but there were things I

01:48:02.120 --> 01:48:07.480
mean I was not comfortable with him on certain politically that is on certain things but at the

01:48:07.480 --> 01:48:14.760
level of public stance you know I loved him and you guys see he just represented like some people

01:48:14.760 --> 01:48:22.920
say that Malcolm does or he did better. A sense of a black particularly black manhood asserting

01:48:22.920 --> 01:48:27.880
itself in a way that was not convenient or comfortable for the white mainstream society.

01:48:27.880 --> 01:48:37.160
Take me forward from your conversation with Carmichael in 66 through well of course we're

01:48:37.160 --> 01:48:43.240
gonna we're gonna encounter the New York rebellion in the summer of 77. 67. Excuse me, 67th

01:48:43.240 --> 01:48:53.800
of course and Carmichael departs Nick in 67 and then your brown will come in. Yeah kind of

01:48:53.800 --> 01:49:00.680
talking through that that's a lot to talk about. Well one thing I did in in 66 as part of that

01:49:00.680 --> 01:49:08.680
interchange is Stokely one of people who he knew to travel with him so I went on several trips with

01:49:08.680 --> 01:49:13.400
him I mean he was speaking for what was that time was making money a thousand dollars of

01:49:13.400 --> 01:49:21.320
speaking gauge which Nick badly needed. Everybody went up to to Seattle Washington to the university

01:49:21.320 --> 01:49:25.400
there and I remember going to with Charles Lloyd concert just a matter of record kind of Charles

01:49:25.400 --> 01:49:31.640
Lloyd. We went up to Bard College in New York State and then I went to the university with

01:49:31.640 --> 01:49:42.040
him with him in in journalism Milwaukee or Madison I think it was yeah no that's right I'm

01:49:42.040 --> 01:49:47.880
tempted to say Milwaukee because I remember there was this Locust Street that seemed to be everywhere

01:49:47.880 --> 01:49:53.560
it was the main street. Everywhere we always came back on Locust and I think that I think I

01:49:53.560 --> 01:49:58.520
think I was in Milwaukee but in the process of flying out and talking we'd have a lot of conversation

01:49:58.520 --> 01:50:05.800
on the plane and and then after whatever the activity days event we'd kind of debrief

01:50:06.840 --> 01:50:17.000
and with the bar trip cleave sellers went up with us and then Stokely was being mobbed and so he'd

01:50:17.000 --> 01:50:22.520
always be saying well you know was I too strong on this so what was I not strong enough or should

01:50:22.520 --> 01:50:27.640
I have emphasized this or that and so it was like getting into like what's the messaging and what

01:50:27.640 --> 01:50:33.480
is it we're trying to say but it's from the from the person who's at the very point of doing it you

01:50:33.480 --> 01:50:40.920
know and so I mean that was a kind of unique spot and and just because of the again the

01:50:40.920 --> 01:50:48.520
nag experience and I mean he knew that we were going to be both totally friendly and support

01:50:48.520 --> 01:51:00.120
but also critical you know it's like you know you know we'll come back to Carmichael and his

01:51:00.120 --> 01:51:07.720
vision that's Nick and put me to ask about the you were in Newark in July of 67

01:51:09.720 --> 01:51:18.360
in fact I got to visit to Cleveland a week before my folks and my dad who never quite made that

01:51:18.360 --> 01:51:23.400
radical stuff I remember he said oh you got back just in time to start the riot didn't you

01:51:23.400 --> 01:51:32.040
yeah my dad unfortunately became who had been as I said earlier this conversation with great

01:51:32.040 --> 01:51:41.320
inspiration for me as we the 60s progress we had less and less real conversation he just really

01:51:42.360 --> 01:51:48.680
he couldn't go beyond the certain point and we had gone beyond that and the fact that his son

01:51:48.680 --> 01:51:54.680
was doing it the first person the family who had a chance to complete a college education I dropped

01:51:54.680 --> 01:52:00.600
out of school for 11 years we didn't go back until 75 which was after this time period we're talking

01:52:00.600 --> 01:52:07.480
about it's after he died too he died 74 he just got he thought that was wasting my life he said are

01:52:07.480 --> 01:52:12.200
you are you happy working for mr. Castro and just you know mr. this and this and

01:52:12.600 --> 01:52:19.160
well that I guess to say that is to make that very important point that there are very substantial

01:52:19.160 --> 01:52:23.080
personal costs that come in a life of commitment that you have left yeah yeah

01:52:25.960 --> 01:52:30.520
the thing with my mother was funny she was also opposed to it a lot of the stuff but

01:52:31.240 --> 01:52:37.320
and I used to come home and she she she always have this conversation but the way she'd look at me

01:52:37.320 --> 01:52:42.200
she always could have looked at it was like him here up my hair afro and wasn't until

01:52:42.200 --> 01:52:48.440
ebony magazine did a whole thing on the new cultural of the 60s in the afro that she finally

01:52:48.440 --> 01:52:52.600
relented and said well as long as you cut it and keep it shaped it's all right you know but

01:52:53.640 --> 01:52:59.320
but she was very much concerned with how the parents and how people think and stuff like that

01:53:00.120 --> 01:53:08.760
is your reaction to Newark to Newark? Well I mean I think we participated you know I was out

01:53:08.760 --> 01:53:13.800
of the streets to in the Newark rebellion we are actually as I said was part of this more racial

01:53:14.360 --> 01:53:20.680
against the white power structure is well let's just say what happened I got back from Cleveland

01:53:20.680 --> 01:53:26.680
I had just developed this friendship with a lady who was a vista volunteer and she was over in the

01:53:26.680 --> 01:53:34.120
North Ward and she was from actually from well with New Jersey beach town further so and I'd

01:53:34.120 --> 01:53:41.080
get over to visit her and I stayed until a little bit after midnight and I suddenly told

01:53:41.080 --> 01:53:47.560
me I should go home back to the North I was living in the sensual ward on 18th Avenue and so I

01:53:47.560 --> 01:53:54.920
as I was walking back at night as a very few cars out and then I was I heard police sirens and then I

01:53:54.920 --> 01:54:02.520
heard cracks and stuff was a gunshot somebody shooting at somebody and so I kept walking back and

01:54:02.520 --> 01:54:09.000
so I got back over to the 18th Ward I mean 80th Avenue in the sensual ward and people tell me the

01:54:09.000 --> 01:54:14.200
whole all hell had broken loose and it broke and loose at the police station which was just one block

01:54:14.200 --> 01:54:18.920
away from where I lived on 17th Avenue and where they had captured this guy forget his name now John

01:54:19.560 --> 01:54:26.120
he was a taxi driver and they had put him inside and and the people were outside the police station

01:54:26.120 --> 01:54:31.400
and then they said I'm throwing rocks and bricks and stuff like that and what happened is because

01:54:32.840 --> 01:54:40.360
I lived the block away but more importantly and so I was right there at the scene is that there

01:54:40.360 --> 01:54:48.680
was this guy named BJ and BJ was a community character who grew up in the sensual ward and the

01:54:48.680 --> 01:54:55.320
minute I saw the movie Zorba the Greek that's BJ so if you ever saw that movie with the kind

01:54:55.320 --> 01:55:01.800
of character Zorba was this is what BJ was and and he and I lived together because what happened is

01:55:01.800 --> 01:55:06.680
we got an office in the sensual ward whose windows would get broken out by the local democrats

01:55:06.680 --> 01:55:14.760
but right next door he had a place and I moved in remember we had a tub tub a tub right in the kitchen

01:55:14.840 --> 01:55:25.400
and it was old fashioned but he knew everybody and so I mean my ability to be there and organize

01:55:25.400 --> 01:55:32.520
and meet people and get accepted was through BJ and so when we went out that night on 17th Avenue

01:55:32.520 --> 01:55:38.680
is like what's happening is he knew people I knew people but I knew people basically through him

01:55:39.560 --> 01:55:47.240
and we said look looks like something big is happening here it's we heard it was spreading over on

01:55:47.240 --> 01:55:52.920
springful Avenue which was one of the main streets and we said let's not try to stop this

01:55:53.960 --> 01:56:00.680
but let's what we do is we're only going to attack things that are white-owned because we want to

01:56:00.680 --> 01:56:05.800
get the white domination white ownership out of the black community and which forced a lot of

01:56:05.800 --> 01:56:09.480
store owners to start saying even some white folks said put other windows black home black home

01:56:09.480 --> 01:56:14.760
you know after they caught up on the second night or so but I guess what I'm say that is that we

01:56:15.400 --> 01:56:21.080
didn't want to have people be seen go out go out while they do and stuff and is that we were

01:56:21.080 --> 01:56:26.280
we had a very much of a clear intent and so this was even different within the stick because I remember

01:56:26.280 --> 01:56:31.480
my friends in Detroit snake and basically told people to get off the streets and they had no street

01:56:32.200 --> 01:56:37.960
and so we were right there actually got beat up by the police that night well the second night

01:56:39.240 --> 01:56:44.120
because what happened is it's really stupid we were there were some housing projects right

01:56:44.120 --> 01:56:54.920
near the 17th Avenue called the Hayes homes and I have no idea if they're still standing but I

01:56:54.920 --> 01:57:03.400
saw a bunch of policemen and being cocky and young and totally stupid I yelled black power like

01:57:03.400 --> 01:57:10.920
this was what was happening and they said stop right there so I had about less than two seconds

01:57:10.920 --> 01:57:15.640
to figure out whether I could run fast enough to get into the projects because I knew once I got

01:57:15.640 --> 01:57:22.280
the projects they never find me but the question is how would they chase me how fast their guns

01:57:22.280 --> 01:57:28.120
could shoot how good so I decided well I think I'm going to stay here I'm not going to run

01:57:28.120 --> 01:57:33.400
I'm not going to take that risk so all of a sudden I was with a guy from the neighborhood got

01:57:33.400 --> 01:57:41.160
named Joe Whitley who was a bartender at a bar in the Central Ward and they stopped us and they

01:57:41.160 --> 01:57:46.920
said now what did you say and these are eight really big guys they're all bigger than both me and Joe

01:57:47.560 --> 01:57:54.200
and so in some of the squeaky voice I said black power because I couldn't recant when I had said

01:57:54.200 --> 01:58:00.280
but you know this was totally intimidating they had guns and everything and so they grabbed us

01:58:00.920 --> 01:58:06.600
and what was really interesting is both then and hindsight they beat us but what they did was

01:58:06.600 --> 01:58:13.480
they used rubber trunches they didn't use anything that would leave marks and so they just came

01:58:13.560 --> 01:58:18.600
and turned us around hit us hit us like this all this and what happened is this is where the

01:58:18.600 --> 01:58:24.200
earlier civil rights training really paid off back of the non-violent days because I knew how to turn

01:58:24.200 --> 01:58:30.280
and lean and you know so that they couldn't get in here and all that stuff and protect my head

01:58:30.280 --> 01:58:36.840
and so I'll absorb some of the blows my friend Joe didn't so what happened is that they left us

01:58:36.840 --> 01:58:41.880
there Joe was lying lying on the sidewalk you know I was on the sidewalk but I bounced up and

01:58:42.440 --> 01:58:48.840
and so and I had to take him home essentially and then once I was really mad I did and so we ended up

01:58:49.400 --> 01:58:55.640
going into one of the neighborhood bars and just and just take of course this is where the

01:58:55.640 --> 01:59:01.160
looting part came in because all these beer kids people just say hey we're all the

01:59:01.160 --> 01:59:06.040
the term was we're gonna liberate that you know take it over to my house we're gonna consume it but

01:59:06.360 --> 01:59:14.200
so it was a very you know I could have gotten killed easily that night and then about two nights

01:59:14.200 --> 01:59:21.560
later I was they could they had a curfew and so I was out past a curfew on South Florida Javanagh

01:59:21.560 --> 01:59:28.920
and so I had to get in call on around some community resources to I didn't have cell phone

01:59:28.920 --> 01:59:33.640
we've had cell phone them it wasn't great I gotta call a few people gotten so I just not

01:59:33.640 --> 01:59:38.520
got a couple doors and I said I'm with the newer group and we've been working around you know black

01:59:40.120 --> 01:59:46.280
support and so the rides and by power and could I stay here for a while and they let me in

01:59:47.080 --> 01:59:50.440
if not I would have been out in the street there were snipers out in the street we actually knew

01:59:50.440 --> 01:59:57.080
a couple of snipers who who were firing on the cops but we weren't doing that but I didn't want

01:59:57.080 --> 02:00:00.840
to get caught in the middle of that either so I mean they let me in so that was the night that I

02:00:00.840 --> 02:00:05.240
got saved and from being out in the street so there were several you know occasions like that

02:00:05.240 --> 02:00:15.060
that you know will it happen during the North

02:00:15.060 --> 02:00:21.860
and then sitting up in this and there were some older black woman I could hear in the back of them

02:00:21.860 --> 02:00:26.900
they were talking about all the stuff that happened last night and she said it's about time they did

02:00:26.900 --> 02:00:32.660
this they've been doing it around the country and it's about time to do it here and so that kept me

02:00:32.660 --> 02:00:38.820
that our message and our campaigns of the six to eight months previous to that in terms of the

02:00:38.820 --> 02:00:43.940
racial prologue rising around white control not necessarily just white people but with the white

02:00:43.940 --> 02:00:49.140
control had had some positive effect because I remember in a couple other places Cleveland being one

02:00:49.140 --> 02:00:53.780
of them at home time when they went to have the half-grabelian there was a very apologetic we just you know

02:00:54.660 --> 02:01:00.820
we we we acted like animals we just overacted it that's why we made sure to say this was a rebellion

02:01:00.820 --> 02:01:08.580
not just a riot making those distinctions in terms of the organizing so that people who had stood up

02:01:08.660 --> 02:01:14.340
in a slightly unusual way you know felt that they had they at manifested something important and

02:01:14.340 --> 02:01:19.940
and and feeling good good about it which is one of the reasons why the state police really felt that

02:01:19.940 --> 02:01:28.820
we were had a real hand in promoting and being a part of the rebellion the massive police response

02:01:29.140 --> 02:01:37.460
did you did you emerge from that it sounds as if you emerge from that five days

02:01:40.020 --> 02:01:48.820
feeling more inspired by the example of this self assertion of black community you did

02:01:51.460 --> 02:01:57.940
discouraged by the state's capacity to respond yes definitely in fact we were hoping the state

02:01:57.940 --> 02:02:03.060
wouldn't have a good capacity to respond they would have put us in jail I guess that would have

02:02:03.060 --> 02:02:09.220
probably probably some of the proper response or and of course they were of course all these

02:02:09.220 --> 02:02:14.180
commissions that came afterwards they were set up I can't remember the big one in New Jersey to

02:02:14.180 --> 02:02:22.340
investigate what had happened and why this had happened and etc etc etc but we felt that the

02:02:23.060 --> 02:02:26.820
the go from so where do we want to go from there I mean because that's from the organizer's

02:02:26.820 --> 02:02:32.500
standpoint okay we had the great mass revolt out in the street we did something totally unprecedented

02:02:32.500 --> 02:02:38.260
and where do we go from now yeah so let's make this an opportunity to go for black political power

02:02:38.820 --> 02:02:45.060
and it's out of that kid in the idea getting the black mayor and so we had begun this earlier on in

02:02:45.060 --> 02:02:56.820
some ways in 1966 there has been a mayoral election yeah 66 yeah and we couldn't get quite

02:02:56.820 --> 02:03:03.940
unity for for who should run for mayor of course from the black candidate and so George Richardson

02:03:03.940 --> 02:03:09.860
who had been a state assemblyman and lived in the work wanted to run and so what he did was

02:03:09.860 --> 02:03:16.260
but he wanted a power base kind of like Bill Nolan ever on the right to work they so instead of

02:03:16.260 --> 02:03:23.380
running for mayor he wanted a power base so he ran for central war councilman and we and we put

02:03:23.380 --> 02:03:29.300
up just like the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party put up the mock election for government back

02:03:29.300 --> 02:03:35.780
in and what was that 63 as we did something for mayor we we said let's we have to have a black

02:03:35.780 --> 02:03:40.340
mayoral candidate you get people thinking about voting for a black man for mayor so we found

02:03:40.340 --> 02:03:47.780
this guy named Ken Gibson who was a civil engineer he seemed to be very he was middle class that

02:03:47.780 --> 02:03:54.820
excessively but clearly that's where he came out of didn't have any great foreign policy policies

02:03:54.820 --> 02:04:00.980
around a lot of stuff but didn't have any real guard I mean track record in a negative way either

02:04:00.980 --> 02:04:04.820
and he hadn't antagonized many folks in the black community so we put up for him for black mayor

02:04:05.780 --> 02:04:15.300
he lost but he got a credible amount of votes and and so what happened though in 1970

02:04:15.300 --> 02:04:20.740
meaning after that is in Richard some decided he really wants to run for mayor and so does Gibson

02:04:20.740 --> 02:04:26.660
now and so we that's why we had a political convention so that there would be a candidate that

02:04:26.660 --> 02:04:32.020
comes out of the black community it's actually the black and Puerto Rican because we were at that time

02:04:32.100 --> 02:04:37.140
being noticed that there were more and more Puerto Ricans living there was a woman named Ilda Ildago

02:04:37.140 --> 02:04:44.740
who had been very supportive around a lot of the black causes and realizing that the Puerto Ricans

02:04:44.740 --> 02:04:51.860
had more at stake with the black community there and so that there was that link early on so we had

02:04:51.860 --> 02:04:56.980
this black and Puerto Rican convention and we nominated Ken Gibson for for mayor and then

02:04:57.700 --> 02:05:04.660
that was early 70 I think I can't remember either late 69 early 70 and then of course the election

02:05:04.660 --> 02:05:13.140
was in 70 and then he ran for mayor and one and I say the other side I don't total arrogance

02:05:14.660 --> 02:05:18.820
there were four Italians who ran against them I mean they just assumed that they could

02:05:18.820 --> 02:05:24.820
beat any black per candidate so they ran for them and of course they split the vote and Gibson

02:05:24.900 --> 02:05:25.540
what easily

02:05:29.460 --> 02:05:35.220
let me put you back to one other very significant outcome post July of 67

02:05:38.260 --> 02:05:41.860
you will work with Nathan Wright to organize the first black convention

02:05:47.380 --> 02:05:53.620
can you describe that process that effort to bring that together and what

02:05:55.540 --> 02:06:02.980
the vision that animated that convention and what you saw looking at from the moment

02:06:04.580 --> 02:06:09.380
well I think part of the vision was how do you go from community power to broader urban power

02:06:10.180 --> 02:06:16.900
